INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2,1,'2009-11-13 14:07:02','2009-11-13 14:07:02','This is my web development learning journal. It\'s a place for me to store useful code and information that I work with so I can refer back to it in the future. It\'s also a learning tool because writing down a problem or solution makes me think about it logically and helps me to understand it.\r\n\r\nI\'m a web developer and I work at <a title=\"The Cubeworks site\" href=\"http://www.cubeworks.co.uk\">Cubeworks </a>in <a title=\"Brighton on the map\" href=\"http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=brighton,+uk&amp;sll=53.800651,-4.064941&amp;sspn=20.824402,57.084961&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=Brighton,+East+Sussex,+United+Kingdom&amp;ll=50.819818,-0.131836&amp;spn=22.241089,57.084961&amp;z=5\">Brighton</a>.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-292\" title=\"Jonathan Sewell\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/DSCF3927_small.jpg\" alt=\"Jonathan Sewell\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" />','About','','publish','open','open','','about','','','2010-11-29 20:19:50','2010-11-29 20:19:50','',0,'http://localhost/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(3,1,'2009-11-17 14:02:22','2009-11-17 14:02:22','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\r\n\r\nHere\'s what I did:\r\n\r\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\r\n\r\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Wordpress in a lunch break','','draft','open','open','','wordpress-in-a-lunch-break','','','2010-06-29 14:27:30','2010-06-29 13:27:30','',0,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/?p=3',0,'post','',0),(4,1,'2009-11-17 14:01:40','2009-11-17 14:01:40','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\n\nHere\'s what I did:\n\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\n<ul>\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\n</ul>\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\n\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Lunch break Wordpressing','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision','','','2009-11-17 14:01:40','2009-11-17 14:01:40','',3,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/index.php/2009/11/17/3-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(5,1,'2009-11-17 14:02:22','2009-11-17 14:02:22','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\r\n\r\nHere\'s what I did:\r\n\r\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\r\n\r\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-2','','','2009-11-17 14:02:22','2009-11-17 14:02:22','',3,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/index.php/2009/11/17/3-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(6,1,'2010-02-27 21:49:51','2010-02-27 21:49:51','<p>I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\n<p>Here\'s what I did:</p>\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\n','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-autosave','','','2010-02-27 21:49:51','2010-02-27 21:49:51','',3,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/index.php/2009/11/17/3-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(10,1,'2010-01-06 16:04:38','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Login with return Url','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-01-06 16:04:38','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=10',0,'post','',0),(13,1,'2010-01-22 13:34:37','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Shift + Alt + L Â  Â Locate in Solution Explorer\n\nShift + Alt + F11 Highlight usages in file','My Favourite Resharper Shortcuts','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-01-22 13:34:37','2010-01-22 13:34:37','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=13',0,'post','',0),(14,1,'2010-01-13 14:36:53','2010-01-13 14:36:53','Shift + Alt + L Â  Â Locate in Solution Explorer','My Favourite Resharper Shortcuts','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision','','','2010-01-13 14:36:53','2010-01-13 14:36:53','',13,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/13/13-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(17,1,'2010-01-18 17:13:44','2010-01-18 17:13:44','Shift + Alt + L Â  Â Locate in Solution Explorer\n\nSHift + Alt + F11 Highlight','My Favourite Resharper Shortcuts','','inherit','open','open','','13-revision-2','','','2010-01-18 17:13:44','2010-01-18 17:13:44','',13,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/18/13-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2010-01-19 11:07:30','2010-01-19 11:07:30','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n		{\r\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n		};\r\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n</pre>\r\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that you can go back to the landing page and select a new country.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','draft','open','open','','using-cookies-to-redirect-a-user-to-the-last-page-they-visted','','','2010-06-29 14:27:32','2010-06-29 13:27:32','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=18',0,'post','',0),(19,1,'2010-01-19 11:00:19','2010-01-19 11:00:19','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\n\nCode for the country home page template\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n					{\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n					};\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\n\n	if (!IsPostBack)\n		DataBind();\n}</pre>\nCode for the global home page','','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision','','','2010-01-19 11:00:19','2010-01-19 11:00:19','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/19/18-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(20,1,'2010-01-19 11:06:58','2010-01-19 11:06:58','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\n\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n					{\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n					};\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\n\n	if (!IsPostBack)\n		DataBind();\n}</pre>\n<strong>Code for the global home page</strong>\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\n{\n	//redirect away from this map page to the last country page\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\n	var isNotAdminUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsadmin\");\n	var isNotEditUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsedit\");\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\n\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; isNotAdminUrl &amp;&amp; isNotEditUrl &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\n	{\n		//redirect to last country page\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\n	}\n}</pre>\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that:\n<ol>\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from a country home page they are not sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\n</ol>\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.','','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-2','','','2010-01-19 11:06:58','2010-01-19 11:06:58','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/19/18-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(21,1,'2010-03-27 13:24:02','2010-03-27 13:24:02','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\n		{\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\n		};\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);</pre>\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\n\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\n	{\n		//redirect to last country page\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\n	}</pre>\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that you can go back to the landing page and select a new country.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-autosave','','','2010-03-27 13:24:02','2010-03-27 13:24:02','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/03/18-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(22,1,'2010-01-19 11:07:30','2010-01-19 11:07:30','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\r\n\r\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\r\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n					{\r\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n					};\r\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n\r\n	if (!IsPostBack)\r\n		DataBind();\r\n}</pre>\r\n<strong>Code for the global home page</strong>\r\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	//redirect away from this map page to the last country page\r\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotAdminUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsadmin\");\r\n	var isNotEditUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsedit\");\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; isNotAdminUrl &amp;&amp; isNotEditUrl &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from a country home page they are not sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-3','','','2010-01-19 11:07:30','2010-01-19 11:07:30','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/01/19/18-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(23,1,'2010-02-26 23:52:50','2010-02-26 23:52:50','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\r\n\r\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n					{\r\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n					};\r\n	Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n\r\n	if (!IsPostBack)\r\n		DataBind();\r\n}</pre>\r\n<strong>Code for the global home page</strong>\r\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	//redirect away from this map page to the last country page\r\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotAdminUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsadmin\");\r\n	var isNotEditUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsedit\");\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; isNotAdminUrl &amp;&amp; isNotEditUrl &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from a country home page they are not sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-4','','','2010-02-26 23:52:50','2010-02-26 23:52:50','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/26/18-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(24,1,'2010-02-27 00:04:19','2010-02-27 00:04:19','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\r\n\r\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n					{\r\n						Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n						Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n					};\