rit','open','open','','18-revision-6','','','2010-02-27 00:06:19','2010-02-27 00:06:19','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/18-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(26,1,'2010-02-27 20:58:59','2010-02-27 20:58:59','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page.\r\n\r\n<strong>Code for the country home page template</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nprotected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	var aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n		{\r\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n		};\r\n		Response.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n\r\n	if (!IsPostBack)\r\n	DataBind();\r\n}\r\n</pre>\r\n<strong>Code for the global home page</strong>\r\n<pre>protected void Page_Load(object sender, System.EventArgs e)\r\n{\r\n	//redirect away from this map page to the last country page\r\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotAdminUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsadmin\");\r\n	var isNotEditUrl = !Page.Request.RawUrl.ToLower(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture).Contains(\"letsedit\");\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; isNotAdminUrl &amp;&amp; isNotEditUrl &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from a country home page they are not sent straight back to the country home page (in a loop)</li>\r\n	<li>If a user navigates to the global home page from outside the website, they are redirected to the last country home page theyÂ visited.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nWe are also not redirecting if the user isÂ editingÂ via the CMS, as this would stop them from editing theÂ globalÂ home page, as they would be redirected.<!--more-->','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-7','','','2010-02-27 20:58:59','2010-02-27 20:58:59','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/18-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(27,1,'2009-11-17 14:03:04','2009-11-17 14:03:04','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\r\n\r\nHere\'s what I did:\r\n\r\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\r\n\r\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-3','','','2009-11-17 14:03:04','2009-11-17 14:03:04','',3,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2009/11/17/3-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(28,1,'2010-02-27 21:46:46','2010-02-27 21:46:46','<p>I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s what I did:</p>\r\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\r\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\r\n','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-4','','','2010-02-27 21:46:46','2010-02-27 21:46:46','',3,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/3-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(29,1,'2010-02-27 22:28:52','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I spoke to a good friend of mine last week who told me his fiancee wanted to build a website and maybe try to get into web design or development.\r\n\r\nAs a web developer there was a huge amount of advice I wanted to give him there and then, and of course he was completely lost after the first 30 seconds!\r\n\r\nSo I\'m going to make a list here of some of the most important things a starting-out web developer should know about.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Standards</li>\r\n	<li>Browser compatibility and testing</li>\r\n	<li>Firefox addons</li>\r\n	<li>Source control</li>\r\n</ul>','Web development tools','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-02-27 22:28:52','2010-02-27 22:28:52','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=29',0,'post','',0),(30,1,'2010-02-27 22:16:42','2010-02-27 22:16:42','I spoke to a good friend of mine last week who told me his fiancee wanted to build a website and maybe try to get into web design or development.\n\nAs a web developer there was a huge amount of advice I wanted to give him there and then, and of course he was completely lost after the first 30 seconds!\n\nSo I\'m going to make a list here of some of the most important things a starting-out web developer should know about.\n<ul>\n	<li>Standards</li>\n	<li>Browser compatibility and testing</li>\n	<li>Firefox addons</li>\n	<li>Source control</li>\n</ul>','Web development tools','','inherit','open','open','','29-revision','','','2010-02-27 22:16:42','2010-02-27 22:16:42','',29,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/29-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(31,1,'2010-03-27 13:56:56','2010-03-27 13:56:56','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nI need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else when I don\'t want them to be.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\r\n\r\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\r\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis will create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\r\n\r\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','publish','open','open','','branching-with-tortoise-svn','','','2010-07-03 10:49:54','2010-07-03 09:49:54','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=31',0,'post','',0),(32,1,'2010-03-27 13:24:01','2010-03-27 13:24:01','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\n\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\n\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created.\n\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You use the svn copy command to copy the trunk to a new branch.\n$ svn copy http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/trunk \\</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 100px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/branches/my-calc-branch \\</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 100px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">-m \"Creating a private branch of /calc/trunk.\"</div>\n$ svn copy http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/trunk \\ http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/branches/my-calc-branch \\\n-m \"Creating a private branch of /calc/trunk.\"\n\n<strong>References:</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\n\n<strong>http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision','','','2010-03-27 13:24:01','2010-03-27 13:24:01','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/27/31-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(33,1,'2010-03-27 13:25:01','2010-03-27 13:25:01','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\n\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\n\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created.\n\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You use the svn copy command to copy the trunk to a new branch.\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">$ svn copy http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/trunk   http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/branches/my-calc-branch -m \"Creating a private branch of /calc/trunk.\"</pre>\n<strong>References:</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\n\n<strong>http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-2','','','2010-03-27 13:25:01','2010-03-27 13:25:01','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/27/31-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(34,1,'2010-03-27 13:25:09','2010-03-27 13:25:09','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You use the svn copy command to copy the trunk to a new branch.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">$ svn copy http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/trunk</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">http://svn.example.com/repos/calc/branches/my-calc-branch</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">-m \"Creating a private branch of /calc/trunk.\"</pre>\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-3','','','2010-03-27 13:25:09','2010-03-27 13:25:09','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/27/31-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(35,1,'2010-03-31 14:20:49','2010-03-31 13:20:49','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.</blockquote>\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">CurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','publish','open','open','','datetime-tostring-and-currentculture','','','2010-07-11 11:00:15','2010-07-11 10:00:15','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=35',0,'post','',0),(36,1,'2010-03-31 13:41:53','2010-03-31 12:41:53','','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision','','','2010-03-31 13:41:53','2010-03-31 12:41:53','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(37,1,'2010-03-31 14:03:03','2010-03-31 13:03:03','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising). \n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at \n\nThread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName\n\nAnd that\n((DateTime) CurrentItem.Published).ToLongDateString()\nBrowser language set to French','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-2','','','2010-03-31 14:03:03','2010-03-31 13:03:03','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(38,1,'2010-03-31 14:06:29','2010-03-31 13:06:29','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising). \n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\n\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\n\n<configuration>\n<system.web>\n<globalization culture=\"ru-RU\" uiCulture=\"ru-RU\" />\n</system.web>\n</configuration>\n\n((DateTime) CurrentItem.Published).ToLongDateString()\n','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-3','','','2010-03-31 14:06:29','2010-03-31 13:06:29','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(39,1,'2010-03-31 14:14:45','2010-03-31 13:14:45','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\n\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute.</blockquote>\nenables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.\n\n((DateTime) CurrentItem.Published).ToLongDateString()','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-4','','','2010-03-31 14:14:45','2010-03-31 13:14:45','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(40,1,'2010-03-31 14:19:50','2010-03-31 13:19:50','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\n\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;configuration&gt;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;system.web&gt;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;globalization culture=\"ru-RU\" uiCulture=\"ru-RU\" /&gt;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/system.web&gt;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/configuration&gt;</div>\n&lt;configuration&gt;\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\nThat fixed my bug and the\n\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-5','','','2010-03-31 14:19:50','2010-03-31 13:19:50','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(41,1,'2010-03-31 14:20:49','2010-03-31 13:20:49','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;configuration&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;system.web&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;globalization culture=\"ru-RU\" uiCulture=\"ru-RU\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/system.web&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/configuration&gt;</div>\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-6','','','2010-03-31 14:20:49','2010-03-31 13:20:49','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(42,1,'2010-03-31 14:21:55','2010-03-31 13:21:55','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;configuration&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;system.web&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;globalization culture=\"ru-RU\" uiCulture=\"ru-RU\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/system.web&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 102px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\">&lt;/configuration&gt;</div>\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-7','','','2010-03-31 14:21:55','2010-03-31 13:21:55','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(43,1,'2010-03-31 14:22:40','2010-03-31 13:22:40','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-8','','','2010-03-31 14:22:40','2010-03-31 13:22:40','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(44,1,'2010-03-31 14:25:09','2010-03-31 13:25:09','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-revision-9','','','2010-03-31 14:25:09','2010-03-31 13:25:09','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(45,1,'2010-04-08 17:37:58','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<strong>Mocks</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>A mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\r\n\r\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong></strong>A stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\r\n\r\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.</span></strong>\r\n\r\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\r\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\r\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>MvcContrib.TestHelper</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">MvcContrib contains some helper methods</span> </strong>specifically for MVC controller testing. More information here: <a href=\"http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html\">http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html</a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Rhino.Mocks</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using the MockRepository object to create my stubs. </span></strong></span></strong>','Unit Testing Controllers with Mocks and Stubs','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-04-08 17:37:58','2010-04-08 16:37:58','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=45',0,'post','',0),(46,1,'2010-04-08 15:08:27','2010-04-08 14:08:27','<strong>Mocks</strong>\nA mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\n\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\nA stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\n\nRhino Mocks\n\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer</strong>\nI\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.\n\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\n<ul>\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\n</ul>','','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision','','','2010-04-08 15:08:27','2010-04-08 14:08:27','',45,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/08/45-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(47,1,'2010-04-08 15:16:54','2010-04-08 14:16:54','<strong>Mocks</strong>\nA mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\n\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\nA stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\n\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer\n<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.</span></strong>\n\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\n<ul>\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>MvcContrib.TestHelper\n<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">MvcContrib contains some helper methods</span> </strong>specifically for MVC controller testing. More information on the blog','Unit Testing Controllers with Mocks and Stubs','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-2','','','2010-04-08 15:16:54','2010-04-08 14:16:54','',45,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/08/45-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(48,1,'2010-04-08 15:35:32','2010-04-08 14:35:32','<strong>Mocks</strong>\nA mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\n\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\nA stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\n\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer\n<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.</span></strong>\n\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\n<ul>\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>MvcContrib.TestHelper\n<span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">MvcContrib contains some helper methods</span> </strong>specifically for MVC controller testing. More information here: <a href=\"http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html\">http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html</a>\n\nRhino.Mocks','Unit Testing Controllers with Mocks and Stubs','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-3','','','2010-04-08 15:35:32','2010-04-08 14:35:32','',45,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/08/45-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(49,1,'2010-04-08 15:37:15','2010-04-08 14:37:15','<strong>Mocks</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>A mock is an object that mimics another object for the purpose of testing <strong>and </strong>allows you to verify how it was used by setting expectations and verifying them later. It is a kind of <strong>Test Double</strong> (like a move double) with behaviour verification (as opposed to state verification which stubs may do).\n\n<strong>Stubs</strong>\n\n<strong></strong>A stub is a test double that is used to \"provide canned answers to calls made during the test\" (<a href=\"http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html\">http://martinfowler.com/articles/mocksArentStubs.html</a>). It deals with state, not behaviour, and is used in place of aÂ <em>real</em> object to help isolate the test from real objects.\n\n<strong>AutoMockingContainer</strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using an AutoMockingContainer which, given a type, creates a mocked object of that type. The really useful thing is it will satisfy all dependencies for that type <strong>auto</strong>matically.</span></strong>\n\nUsage of our AutoMockingContainer implementation is simple:\n<ul>\n	<li>Call Create&lt;T&gt;() to get the object under test</li>\n	<li>Call Get&lt;T&gt;() to get a mocked object</li>\n	<li>Set expectations on mocked object, act on object under test, verify expectations on mocked object</li>\n</ul>\n<strong>MvcContrib.TestHelper</strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">MvcContrib contains some helper methods</span> </strong>specifically for MVC controller testing. More information here: <a href=\"http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html\">http://blog.stevehorn.cc/2009/06/aspnet-mvc-intro-to-mvccontrib.html</a>\n\n<strong>Rhino.Mocks</strong>\n\n<strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><strong><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">I\'m using the MockRepository object to create my stubs. </span></strong></span></strong>','Unit Testing Controllers with Mocks and Stubs','','inherit','open','open','','45-revision-4','','','2010-04-08 15:37:15','2010-04-08 14:37:15','',45,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/08/45-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(50,1,'2010-04-15 18:02:11','2010-04-15 17:02:11','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleague checks out a version.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','publish','open','open','','creating-a-new-episerver-6-solution','','','2010-05-10 16:24:31','2010-05-10 15:24:31','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=50',0,'post','',0),(51,1,'2010-04-15 12:31:28','2010-04-15 11:31:28','','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision','','','2010-04-15 12:31:28','2010-04-15 11:31:28','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(52,1,'2010-04-15 12:38:32','2010-04-15 11:38:32','Open Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-2','','','2010-04-15 12:38:32','2010-04-15 11:38:32','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(53,1,'2010-04-15 14:36:56','2010-04-15 13:36:56','Open Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database.\n\nCubeworksEPiServer6\n\ncubew0rks','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-3','','','2010-04-15 14:36:56','2010-04-15 13:36:56','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(54,1,'2010-04-15 14:40:39','2010-04-15 13:40:39','Open Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\n\nCubeworksEPiServer6\n!4u2kn0w','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-4','','','2010-04-15 14:40:39','2010-04-15 13:40:39','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(55,1,'2010-07-11 11:01:17','2010-07-11 10:01:17','I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was \"French\", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\n\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;configuration&gt;\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\n        &lt;globalization culture=\"en-GB\" uiCulture=\"en-GB\" /&gt;\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.</blockquote>\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">CurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()</pre>','DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture','','inherit','open','open','','35-autosave','','','2010-07-11 11:01:17','2010-07-11 10:01:17','',35,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/35-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(56,1,'2010-04-15 15:37:48','2010-04-15 14:37:48','<strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong>\n\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\n\nCubeworksEPiServer6\n!4u2kn0w\n\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\n\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer </strong>\n\n<strong>Move the Program Files</strong>\n\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\n\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\n\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think.\n\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\n\nbecomes\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"RelativePathProvider, MyEPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\n\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, which is this:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>return configParameters;</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\n	{\n		public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\n			: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\n		{\n		}\n\n		private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\n		{\n			var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\n\n			if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\n				configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\n\n			return configParameters;\n		}\n	}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\n</span></span></pre>','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-5','','','2010-04-15 15:37:48','2010-04-15 14:37:48','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(57,1,'2010-04-15 15:37:49','2010-04-15 14:37:49','<strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong>\r\n\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nCubeworksEPiServer6\r\n!4u2kn0w\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Move the Program Files</strong>\r\n\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think.\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"RelativePathProvider, MyEPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, which is this:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>{</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>return configParameters;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n	{\r\n		public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n			: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n		{\r\n		}\r\n\r\n		private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		{\r\n			var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n\r\n			if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n				configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n\r\n			return configParameters;\r\n		}\r\n	}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-6','','','2010-04-15 15:37:49','2010-04-15 14:37:49','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(58,1,'2010-04-15 15:39:00','2010-04-15 14:39:00','<strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong>\n\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\n\nCubeworksEPiServer6\n!4u2kn0w\n\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\n\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer </strong>\n\n<strong>Move the Program Files</strong>\n\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\n\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\n\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think.\n\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\n\nbecomes\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"RelativePathProvider, MyEPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\n\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, which is this:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\n{\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\n	{\n	}\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\n	{\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\n		return configParameters;\n	}\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\n</span></span></pre>','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-7','','','2010-04-15 15:39:00','2010-04-15 14:39:00','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(59,1,'2010-04-15 17:11:38','2010-04-15 16:11:38','<h2><strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong></h2>\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\n\nCubeworksEPiServer6\n!4u2kn0w\n\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\n\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\n<h2><strong>Move the Program Files</strong></h2>\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\n\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\n\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think. <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\n\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\n\nbecomes\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\n\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, you may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website use the new configuration.\n\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\n{\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\n	{\n	}\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\n	{\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\n		return configParameters;\n	}\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\n</span></span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">For the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, simply move them into a folder above the root of the website and modify the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.</span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">Install Public Templates</span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site via IIS).</span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">Start the EPiServer Deployment Center and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.</span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">This should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.</span></pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\n</span></pre>','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-8','','','2010-04-15 17:11:38','2010-04-15 16:11:38','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(60,1,'2010-04-15 18:02:11','2010-04-15 17:02:11','<h2><strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong></h2>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nCubeworksEPiServer6\r\n!4u2kn0w\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h2><strong>Move the Program Files</strong></h2>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think. <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, you may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website use the new configuration.\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, simply move them into a folder above the root of the website and modify the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nCreate a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site via IIS).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer Deployment Center and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-9','','','2010-04-15 18:02:11','2010-04-15 17:02:11','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(61,1,'2010-06-29 14:27:33','2010-06-29 13:27:33','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleague checks out a version.</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\n\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\n\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\n\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\n\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\n\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\n\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\n\nbecomes\n\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\n\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\n\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\n{\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\n	{\n	}\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\n	{\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\n		return configParameters;\n	}\n}</pre>\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\n\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\n\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-autosave','','','2010-06-29 14:27:33','2010-06-29 13:27:33','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/19/50-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(62,1,'2010-04-15 18:02:30','2010-04-15 17:02:30','<h2><strong>Just an EPiServer site</strong></h2>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update teh website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nCubeworksEPiServer6\r\n!4u2kn0w\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h2><strong>Move the Program Files</strong></h2>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less I have to tinker with it the better I think. <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider, you may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website use the new configuration.\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, simply move them into a folder above the root of the website and modify the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nCreate a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site via IIS).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer Deployment Center and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-10','','','2010-04-15 18:02:30','2010-04-15 17:02:30','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/50-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(63,1,'2010-04-19 09:28:26','2010-04-19 08:28:26','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h2>Just an EPiServer site</h2>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h2><strong>Move the Program Files</strong></h2>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think. <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-11','','','2010-04-19 09:28:26','2010-04-19 08:28:26','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/19/50-revision-11/',0,'revision','',0),(64,1,'2010-04-21 11:43:47','2010-04-21 10:43:47','<span> </span>\r\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient value ContactDetails.Account</pre>\r\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\r\n\r\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.','NHibernate Errors','','draft','open','open','','nhibernate-errors','','','2010-06-29 14:27:13','2010-06-29 13:27:13','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=64',0,'post','',0),(65,1,'2010-04-21 11:42:08','2010-04-21 10:42:08','<span> </span>\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient  valueJiscCollections.Core.Domain.ContactDetails.Account</pre>\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\n\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails','NHibernate Errors','','inherit','open','open','','64-revision','','','2010-04-21 11:42:08','2010-04-21 10:42:08','',64,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(66,1,'2010-04-21 11:43:47','2010-04-21 10:43:47','<span> </span>\r\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient  valueJiscCollections.Core.Domain.ContactDetails.Account</pre>\r\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\r\n\r\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.','NHibernate Errors','','inherit','open','open','','64-revision-2','','','2010-04-21 11:43:47','2010-04-21 10:43:47','',64,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(67,1,'2010-04-21 11:47:16','2010-04-21 10:47:16','<span> </span>\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient value ContactDetails.Account</pre>\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\n\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.','NHibernate Errors','','inherit','open','open','','64-autosave','','','2010-04-21 11:47:16','2010-04-21 10:47:16','',64,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2010-04-21 11:46:13','2010-04-21 10:46:13','<span> </span>\r\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient value ContactDetails.Account</pre>\r\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\r\n\r\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.','NHibernate Errors','','inherit','open','open','','64-revision-3','','','2010-04-21 11:46:13','2010-04-21 10:46:13','',64,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(69,1,'2010-04-29 23:32:20','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Well, I\'m trying to learn Swedish at the moment and have endlessÂ pieces of paper listing SwedishÂ vocabulary, verbÂ conjugations, and phrases. So I\'m planning to create a web app that can hold all these words and allow me to do interesting things with them, which will hopefully help me learn more Swedish.\r\n<h3>NHibernate</h3>\r\nI\'m starting by following the NHibernate guide at http://nhforge.org/wikis/howtonh/your-first-nhibernate-based-application.aspx.\r\n\r\nI\'ve downloaded NHibernate and created a solution with a class library projects for data, core domain, and tests.\r\n\r\nThe domain I have in mind is very basic (for now).Â  It consists of entities: Word, Translation, and Language.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Copy the mapping file schema xsd file to the lib directory and reference it in Visual Studio</li>\r\n	<li>Creat e a mapping file for the entity Word in the data project</li>\r\n	<li>Add an id section, with generator set to identity</li>\r\n</ul>','Project: libretto - Step 1 - NHibernate','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-04-29 23:32:20','2010-04-29 22:32:20','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=69',0,'post','',0),(70,1,'2010-04-21 22:37:13','2010-04-21 21:37:13','Well, I\'m trying to learn Swedish at the moment and have endlessÂ pieces of paper listing SwedishÂ vocabulary, verbÂ conjugations, and phrases. So I\'m planning to create a web app that can hold all these words and allow me to do interesting things with them, which will hopefully help me learn more Swedish.\n\nI\'ve created a solution with class library projects for data, core domain, and tests.','Project: libretto - Step 1 - NHibernate','','inherit','open','open','','69-revision','','','2010-04-21 22:37:13','2010-04-21 21:37:13','',69,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/69-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(71,1,'2010-04-19 17:41:52','2010-04-19 16:41:52','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h2>Just an EPiServer site</h2>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h2><strong>Move the Program Files</strong></h2>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-12','','','2010-04-19 17:41:52','2010-04-19 16:41:52','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/19/50-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(72,1,'2010-04-22 11:45:56','2010-04-22 10:45:56','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h2>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h2>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-13','','','2010-04-22 11:45:56','2010-04-22 10:45:56','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/22/50-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(73,1,'2010-04-22 11:46:33','2010-04-22 10:46:33','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\" style=\"position: absolute; left: -10000px; top: 0px; width: 1px; height: 1px; overflow-x: hidden; overflow-y: hidden;\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>}</div>\r\npublic class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}<span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; font-size: small;\"><span style=\"line-height: 19px; white-space: normal;\">\r\n</span></span></pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\"><span style=\"font-family: Georgia, \'Times New Roman\', \'Bitstream Charter\', Times, serif; line-height: 19px; white-space: normal; font-size: 13px;\">\r\n</span></pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-14','','','2010-04-22 11:46:33','2010-04-22 10:46:33','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/22/50-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(74,1,'2010-04-22 11:47:41','2010-04-22 10:47:41','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-15','','','2010-04-22 11:47:41','2010-04-22 10:47:41','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/22/50-revision-15/',0,'revision','',0),(75,1,'2010-04-28 10:18:35','2010-04-28 09:18:35','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex \\d+(?=m)','An example and explaination of a zero-width positive lookahead regex in JavaScript.','publish','open','open','','javascript-regex','','','2010-05-15 23:15:18','2010-05-15 22:15:18','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=75',0,'post','',0),(76,1,'2010-04-28 10:17:49','2010-04-28 09:17:49','<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;</pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">var minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(jiraTime)\n\nif (minutesMatch) {\n	var seconds = minutesMatch[0] * 60;\n	secondsElapsed += parseInt(seconds);\n}</pre>\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\n\\d matches any digit\n\n+ matches one or more\n\n(?=m) is a lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match\n\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision','','','2010-04-28 10:17:49','2010-04-28 09:17:49','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(77,1,'2010-05-15 23:16:22','2010-05-15 22:16:22','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\n\nif (minutesMatch) {\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\n}</pre>\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\n\\d matches any digit\n\n+ matches one or more\n\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\n<h3>References</h3>\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex \\d+(?=m)','An example and explaination of a zero-width positive lookahead regex in JavaScript.','inherit','open','open','','75-autosave','','','2010-05-15 23:16:22','2010-05-15 22:16:22','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(78,1,'2010-04-28 10:18:35','2010-04-28 09:18:35','<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;</pre>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">var minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-2','','','2010-04-28 10:18:35','2010-04-28 09:18:35','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(79,1,'2010-04-28 10:19:50','2010-04-28 09:19:50','<pre class=\"brush:jscript\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-3','','','2010-04-28 10:19:50','2010-04-28 09:19:50','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(80,1,'2010-04-28 10:20:13','2010-04-28 09:20:13','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-4','','','2010-04-28 10:20:13','2010-04-28 09:20:13','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(81,1,'2010-04-29 23:31:57','2010-04-29 22:31:57','Well, I\'m trying to learn Swedish at the moment and have endlessÂ pieces of paper listing SwedishÂ vocabulary, verbÂ conjugations, and phrases. So I\'m planning to create a web app that can hold all these words and allow me to do interesting things with them, which will hopefully help me learn more Swedish.\n<h3>NHibernate</h3>\nI\'m starting by following the NHibernate guide at http://nhforge.org/wikis/howtonh/your-first-nhibernate-based-application.aspx.\n\nI\'ve downloaded NHibernate and created a solution with a class library projects for data, core domain, and tests.\n\nThe domain I have in mind is very basic (for now).Â  It consists of entities: Word, Translation, and Language.\n<ul>\n	<li>Copy the mapping file schema xsd file to the lib directory and reference it in Visual Studio</li>\n	<li>Creat e a mapping file for the entity Word in the data project</li>\n	<li>Add an id section, with generator set to identity</li>\n</ul>','Project: libretto - Step 1 - NHibernate','','inherit','open','open','','69-revision-2','','','2010-04-29 23:31:57','2010-04-29 22:31:57','',69,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/29/69-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(82,1,'2010-04-28 10:34:39','2010-04-28 09:34:39','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-5','','','2010-04-28 10:34:39','2010-04-28 09:34:39','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/28/75-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(83,1,'2010-05-01 11:00:35','2010-05-01 10:00:35','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match. eg. <tt>t(?=s)</tt>matches the secondÂ <tt>t</tt> inÂ <tt>streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>)</tt>.\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-6','','','2010-05-01 11:00:35','2010-05-01 10:00:35','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/01/75-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(84,1,'2010-05-01 11:02:13','2010-05-01 10:02:13','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>).\r\n\r\nIt will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-7','','','2010-05-01 11:02:13','2010-05-01 10:02:13','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/01/75-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(85,1,'2010-07-03 10:01:57','2010-07-03 09:01:57','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nI need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else when I don\'t want them to be.\n\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\n\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\n\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\n\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\n\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\n<ol>\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\n</ol>\nThis will create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\n\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\n\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\n\n<strong>References:</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\n\n<strong>\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-autosave','','','2010-07-03 10:01:57','2010-07-03 09:01:57','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/05/31-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(86,1,'2010-03-27 13:56:56','2010-03-27 13:56:56','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\r\n\r\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\r\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nYou have create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\r\n\r\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-4','','','2010-03-27 13:56:56','2010-03-27 13:56:56','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/27/31-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(87,1,'2010-05-05 23:04:32','0000-00-00 00:00:00','What are Virtual Path Providers?\r\n<blockquote>A virtual path provider provides a means to supply content from locations other than the file system.\r\n<a href=\"http://support.microsoft.com/kb/910441\">http://support.microsoft.com/kb/910441</a></blockquote>','EPiServer Virtual Path Providers (VPP)','','draft','open','open','','episerver-virtual-path-providers','','','2010-05-05 23:04:32','2010-05-05 22:04:32','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=87',0,'post','',0),(88,1,'2010-05-05 22:50:59','2010-05-05 21:50:59','What are Virtual Path Providers?\n<blockquote>A virtual path provider provides a means to supply content from locations other than the file system.\n<a href=\"http://support.microsoft.com/kb/910441\">http://support.microsoft.com/kb/910441</a></blockquote>','EPiServer Virtual Path Providers (VPP)','','inherit','open','open','','87-revision','','','2010-05-05 22:50:59','2010-05-05 21:50:59','',87,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/05/87-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(89,1,'2010-05-06 10:39:54','2010-05-06 09:39:54','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','A work in progress cheat sheet of EPiServer code snippets.','draft','open','open','','episerver-snippets','','','2010-06-29 14:27:38','2010-06-29 13:27:38','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=89',0,'post','',0),(90,1,'2010-05-06 10:39:36','2010-05-06 09:39:36','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">Get PageData from a PageReference:</pre>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision','','','2010-05-06 10:39:36','2010-05-06 09:39:36','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(91,1,'2010-05-06 10:39:54','2010-05-06 09:39:54','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-2','','','2010-05-06 10:39:54','2010-05-06 09:39:54','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(92,1,'2010-06-29 14:27:27','2010-06-29 13:27:27','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\n\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','A work in progress cheat sheet of EPiServer code snippets.','inherit','open','open','','89-autosave','','','2010-06-29 14:27:27','2010-06-29 13:27:27','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(93,1,'2010-05-06 10:40:04','2010-05-06 09:40:04','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-3','','','2010-05-06 10:40:04','2010-05-06 09:40:04','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(94,1,'2010-05-06 14:01:53','2010-05-06 13:01:53','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-4','','','2010-05-06 14:01:53','2010-05-06 13:01:53','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(95,1,'2010-05-06 17:13:36','2010-05-06 16:13:36','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files.\r\n\r\nIf you need to override an existing element you can do so, this works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\nTo avoid conflicts with existing language files you could simply create a new XML element to contain your translations, for example:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;mywebsitename&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/mywebsitename&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','Some notes on the EPiServer language XML files and their correct usage.','publish','open','open','','episerver-translate-and-xml','','','2010-05-15 23:11:41','2010-05-15 22:11:41','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=95',0,'post','',0),(96,1,'2010-05-06 17:13:18','2010-05-06 16:13:18','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files. This works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\n\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\nCalling Translate:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\nFor the XML:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\n      &lt;standard&gt;\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the page culture is English.\n\n<strong>References</strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a></strong>\n\n<strong><a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a></strong>','EPiServer Translate and XML','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision','','','2010-05-06 17:13:18','2010-05-06 16:13:18','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(97,1,'2010-05-06 17:13:36','2010-05-06 16:13:36','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files. This works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a></strong>','EPiServer Translate and XML','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision-2','','','2010-05-06 17:13:36','2010-05-06 16:13:36','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(98,1,'2010-09-08 22:25:26','2010-09-08 21:25:26','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files.\n\nIf you need to override an existing element you can do so, this works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\n\nTo avoid conflicts with existing language files you could simply create a new XML element to contain your translations, for example:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\n      &lt;mywebsitename&gt;\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\n      &lt;/mywebsitename&gt;\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\n\nCalling Translate:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\nFor the XML:\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\n      &lt;standard&gt;\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\n\n<strong>References</strong>\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','Some notes on the EPiServer language XML files and their correct usage.','inherit','open','open','','95-autosave','','','2010-09-08 22:25:26','2010-09-08 21:25:26','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(99,1,'2010-05-06 17:14:37','2010-05-06 16:14:37','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files. This works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision-3','','','2010-05-06 17:14:37','2010-05-06 16:14:37','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(100,1,'2010-05-06 17:33:01','2010-05-06 16:33:01','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files.\r\n\r\nIf you need to override an existing element you can do so, this works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\nTo avoid conflicts with existing language files you could simply create a new XML element to contain your translations, for example:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;mywebsitename&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/mywebsitename&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision-4','','','2010-05-06 17:33:01','2010-05-06 16:33:01','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(101,1,'2010-04-22 12:28:09','2010-04-22 11:28:09','The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-16','','','2010-04-22 12:28:09','2010-04-22 11:28:09','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/22/50-revision-16/',0,'revision','',0),(102,1,'2010-05-10 16:15:07','2010-05-10 15:15:07','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleage checks out a version.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-17','','','2010-05-10 16:15:07','2010-05-10 15:15:07','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/10/50-revision-17/',0,'revision','',0),(103,1,'2010-05-10 16:15:27','2010-05-10 15:15:27','<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"></div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">I\'m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleague checks out a version.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they\'re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won\'t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name=\"UIFiles\" virtualPath=\"~/EPiServer/CMS/\" physicalPath=\"~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS\" type=\"Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site\" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith(\"~\"))\r\n			configParameters[\"physicalPath\"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I\'ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I\'m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select \"Install Public Templates\". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style=\"font-size: 1.5em;\">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set \"Copy Local\" to true.','Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution','','inherit','open','open','','50-revision-18','','','2010-05-10 16:15:27','2010-05-10 15:15:27','',50,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/10/50-revision-18/',0,'revision','',0),(104,1,'2010-06-16 21:53:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<div>MVC Controller Tests</div>\n<ul>\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\n	<li>Test reading entities from the repository into the model\n<ul>\n	<li>Test for when repositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Creating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n	<li>Check PRG pattern used</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Editing entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Test model is populated from repository</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Updating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Deleting entries\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\nCheck out \"all controller test\"','MVC Controller Tests','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-06-16 21:53:33','2010-06-16 20:53:33','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=104',0,'post','',0),(105,1,'2010-05-13 16:37:25','2010-05-13 15:37:25','<ul>\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\n	<li>Read entities from the repository into the model\n<ul>\n	<li>RepositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Creating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository - this involves</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>','','','inherit','open','open','','104-revision','','','2010-05-13 16:37:25','2010-05-13 15:37:25','',104,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/13/104-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(106,1,'2010-05-13 16:59:07','2010-05-13 15:59:07','<div>Institution MVC Tests</div>\n<ul>\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\n	<li>Read entities from the repository into the model\n<ul>\n	<li>RepositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Creating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository - this involves</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>','','','inherit','open','open','','104-revision-2','','','2010-05-13 16:59:07','2010-05-13 15:59:07','',104,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/13/104-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(107,1,'2010-05-14 10:55:01','2010-05-14 09:55:01','<div>MVC Controller Tests</div>\n<ul>\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\n	<li>Test reading entities from the repository into the model\n<ul>\n	<li>Test for when repositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Creating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository - this involves</li>\n	<li>Check PRG pattern used</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Editing entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Test for when repositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\nCheck out \"all controller test\"','','','inherit','open','open','','104-revision-3','','','2010-05-14 10:55:01','2010-05-14 09:55:01','',104,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/14/104-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(108,1,'2010-05-14 12:27:17','2010-05-14 11:27:17','<div>MVC Controller Tests</div>\n<ul>\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\n	<li>Test reading entities from the repository into the model\n<ul>\n	<li>Test for when repositoryÂ returns null</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Creating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n	<li>Check PRG pattern used</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Editing entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Test model is populated from repository</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Updating entities\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n	<li>Deleting entries\n<ul>\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\nCheck out \"all controller test\"','','','inherit','open','open','','104-revision-4','','','2010-05-14 12:27:17','2010-05-14 11:27:17','',104,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/14/104-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(109,1,'2010-05-06 17:38:35','2010-05-06 16:38:35','EPiServer stores language resources in XML file sin the \"lang\" folder of the site.\r\n<blockquote>At startup, your EPiServer site will load all the .xml files in the ~/lang directory, alphabetically. A DOM of all language resources will be built in memory, adding all elements from each .xml file, and then cached for the rest of the application life-time (if you change one of the files, it will automatically trigger a reload.) <em>Source: </em><a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\"><em>http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</em></a></blockquote>\r\nThis means you can add your own XMLÂ languageÂ resources for things like control labels on your templates. It is best practice to leave the EPiServer langauge files intact and create your own files.\r\n\r\nIf you need to override an existing element you can do so, this works particularly well because all the XML files are loaded into a DOM, and any existing elements are overwritten by the later element (alphabetically).\r\n\r\nTo avoid conflicts with existing language files you could simply create a new XML element to contain your translations, for example:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;mywebsitename&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/mywebsitename&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\n<strong>Accessing Translations</strong>\r\n\r\nCalling Translate:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">LanguageManager.Instance.Translate(\"/standard/home\")</pre>\r\nFor the XML:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">&lt;language name=\"English\" id=\"EN\"&gt;\r\n      &lt;standard&gt;\r\n           &lt;home&gt;Home in English&lt;/home&gt;\r\n      &lt;/standard&gt;\r\n &lt;/language&gt;</pre>\r\nThis will output the string \"Home in English\" if the current culture is English.\r\n\r\n<strong>References</strong>\r\n<a href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/\">http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Steve-Celius/Dates/112266/112267/Compare-and-keep-language-files-in-sync/</a>\r\n<a href=\"http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/\">http://danielsaidi.wordpress.com/tag/episerver/</a>','EPiServer Translate and XML','','inherit','open','open','','95-revision-5','','','2010-05-06 17:38:35','2010-05-06 16:38:35','',95,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/95-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(110,1,'2010-05-06 16:56:06','2010-05-06 15:56:06','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-5','','','2010-05-06 16:56:06','2010-05-06 15:56:06','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/06/89-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(111,1,'2010-05-01 11:03:28','2010-05-01 10:03:28','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex','','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-8','','','2010-05-01 11:03:28','2010-05-01 10:03:28','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/01/75-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(112,1,'2010-05-15 23:14:27','2010-05-15 22:14:27','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Minute Regex','An example and explaination of a zero-width positive lookahead regex in JavaScript','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-9','','','2010-05-15 23:14:27','2010-05-15 22:14:27','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/75-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(113,1,'2010-05-15 23:14:50','2010-05-15 22:14:50','<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches \"m\" but doesn\'t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match \"10\" in the string \"2h 10m 30s\"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html\">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>','Javascript Regex \\d+(?=m)','An example and explaination of a zero-width positive lookahead regex in JavaScript','inherit','open','open','','75-revision-10','','','2010-05-15 23:14:50','2010-05-15 22:14:50','',75,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/75-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(114,1,'2010-05-15 23:12:50','2010-05-15 22:12:50','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','A work in progress cheat sheet of EPiServer code snippets','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-6','','','2010-05-15 23:12:50','2010-05-15 22:12:50','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/89-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(118,1,'2010-06-11 15:09:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','I\'m setting up a new project using N2 CMS but don\'t have a clear procedure for downloading and setting up an N2 site. I\'m going to use the MVC templates example site as a starting point so make sure you have ASP.NET MVC 2 installed.\r\n<h3>Downloading the Source</h3>\r\nEither get the latest release from CodePlex atÂ Â <a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a> or get the svn repository url from the N2CMS page on Google Code atÂ <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/\">http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/</a> and get the latest version.Â I prefer to get the svn version because it\'s probably more up to date.Â Next, go to the \"src\"Â folder and run the batch file to build dependencies. Now open the MVC example solution in the folder \"N2.Templates.Mvc\"\r\n<h3>Some Build Errors...</h3>\r\nI got a few build errors related to missing N2 references so I just copied these into the bin folder from the src/wwwroot folder, andÂ referencedÂ them.\r\n<h3>Moving to a New Project</h3>\r\nNow I have the MVC example running I want to copy it to a new project folder and check it into a new source control repository. Copy theN2.Templates.MvcÂ folder from the \"src\" folder, Â you can use Beyond Compare so to filter out the .svn folders.\r\n\r\nI haveÂ rearrangedÂ the Â the folder structure for svn, adding trunk/branches folders, renamed wwwroot to Project.Site and added a lib folder for the project references, and an app folder for any supporting projects.Â Next, commit everything to a new svn repository, excluding the products of builds such as the bin older and contents.\r\nI\'ve also renamed the solution and project files to match the project I\'m working on, and also the assembly name and namespace for the project. Â You can use ReSharper to fix the namespaces in the source (right-click project, refactor, adjust namespaces), but you will also need to do a find and replace across the solution to make sure you change all instances of the old namespace.\r\nI also removed the namespace entries in the web.config system.web, pages, namespaces section because I like to seeÂ explicitÂ import statements, it\'s helps me understand what\'s going on. This does involve fixing the imports in pretty much every template though.\r\n<h3>Locking it down</h3>\r\nThe MVC templates site comes with a great selection of built in page types and parts, as well as example content. Obviously you need to change the example content to fit your project, but you should also disable page types and parts that are not required for the project. Although a client will happy take extra functionality, if you give it to them they\'ll expect it to work the way they want it to and you\'ll just create extra work for yourself. You can easily remove page types and parts using the N2 DisableAttribute on their class definition.\r\n<pre>[Disable]\r\npublic class FaqList : AbstractContentPage, IStructuralPage</pre>\r\n<h4>Themes</h4>\r\nIf you edit the start page in N2 you\'ll see you can select a theme from a drop-down list, this is another feature I don\'t need for this project (as it will only have one theme/design) so I\'ve removed the property from StartPage.cs\r\n<pre>[EditableThemeSelection(\"Theme\", 74, ContainerName = LayoutArea)]\r\npublic string Theme\r\n{\r\nget { return (string)(GetDetail(\"Theme\") ?? string.Empty); }\r\nset { SetDetail(\"Theme\", value); }\r\n}</pre>\r\nAnd also changed the Global.asax.cs to use the WebFormViewEngine instead of the ThemedMasterViewEngine:\r\n<pre>ViewEngines.Engines.Insert(0, new WebFormViewEngine());</pre>\r\n<h4>More things to remove</h4>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>The language menu from TopMenu.ascx</li>\r\n	<li>The site logo from Top.ascx</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3>Organising the styles</h3>\r\nTODO\r\n<h3>Configuring TinyMCE</h3>\r\nTODO\r\n<h3>Deployment Checklist</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>set checkInstallationStatus to false in web.config (&lt;installer checkInstallationStatus=\"false\" /&gt;)</li>\r\n	<li>enable/disable globalization in web.config</li>\r\n	<li>set error reporting email address in web.config</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf\">http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/\">http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/</a>','Creating a new N2 CMS project','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-06-11 15:09:33','2010-06-11 14:09:33','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=118',0,'post','',0),(119,1,'2010-05-27 21:40:54','2010-05-27 20:40:54','First download the source code release from <a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a>. I\'m using the release labelled \"N2 CMS 2.0 RC2 Source Code\"\n\nMake sure you have ASP.NET MVC 2 installed.\n\nUnzip the download and run the \"Prepare Dependencies\" batch file.\n\nYou should now have an examples folder in the\n\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span></strong>\n\n<a 