n	<li>The site logo from Top.ascx</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Organising the styles</h3>\nTODO\n<h3>Configuring TinyMCE</h3>\nTODO\n<h3>Deployment Checklist</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>set checkInstallationStatus to false in web.config (&lt;installer checkInstallationStatus=\"false\" /&gt;)</li>\n	<li>enable/disable globalization in web.config</li>\n	<li>set error reporting email address in web.config</li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf\">http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/\">http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/</a>','Creating a new N2 CMS project','','inherit','open','open','','118-revision-4','','','2010-06-11 14:10:31','2010-06-11 13:10:31','',118,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/11/118-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(134,1,'2010-06-11 14:39:39','2010-06-11 13:39:39','I\'m setting up a new project using N2 CMS but don\'t have a clear procedure for downloading and setting up an N2 site. I\'m going to use the MVC templates example site as a starting point so make sure you have ASP.NET MVC 2 installed.\n<h3>Downloading the Source</h3>\nEither get the latest release from CodePlex atÂ Â <a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a> or get the svn repository url from the N2CMS page on Google Code atÂ <a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/\">http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/</a> and get the latest version.Â I prefer to get the svn version because it\'s probably more up to date.Â Next, go to the \"src\"Â folder and run the batch file to build dependencies. Now open the MVC example solution in the folder \"N2.Templates.Mvc\"\n<h3>Some Build Errors...</h3>\nI got a few build errors related to missing N2 references so I just copied these into the bin folder from the src/wwwroot folder, andÂ referencedÂ them.\n<h3>Moving to a New Project</h3>\nNow I have the MVC example running I want to copy it to a new project folder and check it into a new source control repository. Copy theN2.Templates.MvcÂ folder from the \"src\" folder, Â you can use Beyond Compare so to filter out the .svn folders.\n\nI haveÂ rearrangedÂ the Â the folder structure for svn, adding trunk/branches folders, renamed wwwroot to Project.Site and added a lib folder for the project references, and an app folder for any supporting projects.Â Next, commit everything to a new svn repository, excluding the products of builds such as the bin older and contents.\nI\'ve also renamed the solution and project files to match the project I\'m working on, and also the assembly name and namespace for the project. Â You can use ReSharper to fix the namespaces in the source (right-click project, refactor, adjust namespaces), but you will also need to do a find and replace across the solution to make sure you change all instances of the old namespace.\nI also removed the namespace entries in the web.config system.web, pages, namespaces section because I like to seeÂ explicitÂ import statements, it\'s helps me understand what\'s going on. This does involve fixing the imports in pretty much every template though.\n<h3>Locking it down</h3>\nThe MVC templates site comes with a great selection of built in page types and parts, as well as example content. Obviously you need to change the example content to fit your project, but you should also disable page types and parts that are not required for the project. Although a client will happy take extra functionality, if you give it to them they\'ll expect it to work the way they want it to and you\'ll just create extra work for yourself. You can easily remove page types and parts using the N2 DisableAttribute on their class definition.\n<pre>[Disable]\npublic class FaqList : AbstractContentPage, IStructuralPage</pre>\n<h4>Themes</h4>\nIf you edit the start page in N2 you\'ll see you can select a theme from a drop-down list, this is another feature I don\'t need for this project (as it will only have one theme/design) so I\'ve removed the property from StartPage.cs\n<pre>[EditableThemeSelection(\"Theme\", 74, ContainerName = LayoutArea)]\npublic string Theme\n{\nget { return (string)(GetDetail(\"Theme\") ?? string.Empty); }\nset { SetDetail(\"Theme\", value); }\n}</pre>\nAnd also changed the Global.asax.cs to use the WebFormViewEngine instead of the ThemedMasterViewEngine:\n<pre>ViewEngines.Engines.Insert(0, new WebFormViewEngine());</pre>\n<h4>More things to remove</h4>\n<ul>\n	<li>The language menu from TopMenu.ascx</li>\n	<li>The site logo from Top.ascx</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Organising the styles</h3>\nTODO\n<h3>Configuring TinyMCE</h3>\nTODO\n<h3>Deployment Checklist</h3>\n<ul>\n	<li>set checkInstallationStatus to false in web.config (&lt;installer checkInstallationStatus=\"false\" /&gt;)</li>\n	<li>enable/disable globalization in web.config</li>\n	<li>set error reporting email address in web.config</li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span>\n\n<a href=\"http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf\">http://interferencelogik.com/docs/N2CMS_TheLittleHandbook.pdf</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446\">http://n2cms.codeplex.com/releases/view/44446</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/\">http://code.google.com/p/n2cms/</a>','Creating a new N2 CMS project','','inherit','open','open','','118-revision-5','','','2010-06-11 14:39:39','2010-06-11 13:39:39','',118,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/11/118-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(136,1,'2010-05-14 16:58:38','2010-05-14 15:58:38','<div>MVC Controller Tests</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Test rendering of all views</li>\r\n	<li>Test reading entities from the repository into the model\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Test for when repositoryÂ returns null</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Creating entities\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\r\n	<li>Check PRG pattern used</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Editing entities\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Test model is populated from repository</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Updating entities\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Deleting entries\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Check that all model values are passed to the repository method</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nCheck out \"all controller test\"','','','inherit','open','open','','104-revision-5','','','2010-05-14 16:58:38','2010-05-14 15:58:38','',104,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/14/104-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(137,1,'2010-06-27 22:01:01','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<h2>Setting up LAMP on Ubuntu</h2>\nI want to be able to work on my blog code using myÂ net-book which is currently running Ubuntu (10.04 Lucid Lynx), so I need to get Apache, MySQL, and PHP working. It just takes a few simple steps.\n<ul>\n	<li>Install Apache2 using \"sudo apt-get\" (go to http://localhost/ to test)</li>\n	<li>Install PHP \"sudo apt-get install php5 libapache2-mod-php5\"</li>\n	<li>Test PHP by adding /var/www/testphp.php containing &lt;?php phpinfo(); ?&gt;</li>\n	<li>Install MySQL server \"sudo apt-get install mysql-server\"</li>\n	<li>Install MySQL Administrator (I used the Ubuntu Software Centre)</li>\n</ul>\nNext, create a new site configuration so that Apache can access my website files which are in /home/myusername/Desktop/myblog. This makes it easier to work with the website files as the default Apache site location has higher security restrictions. See the <a title=\"ApacheMySQLPHP Virtual Hosts\" href=\"https://help.ubuntu.com/community/ApacheMySQLPHP#Virtual Hosts\">Ubuntu Documentation</a> for instructions.\n\nSide note on UbuntuÂ terminal commands:\n<ul>\n	<li>the \"sudo\" command gives you root privileges to run a program</li>\n	<li>\"apt-get\" will download and install software packages</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>References</h2>\n<a href=\"http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies\">http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies</a>\n\n<a href=\"https://help.ubuntu.com/community/ApacheMySQLPHP#Virtual Hosts\">https://help.ubuntu.com/community/ApacheMySQLPHP#Virtual Hosts</a>','Developing my Blog','','draft','open','open','','','','','2010-06-27 22:01:01','2010-06-27 21:01:01','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=137',0,'post','',0),(138,1,'2010-06-26 21:53:14','2010-06-26 20:53:14','<h2>Setting up LAMP on Ubuntu</h2>\nI want to be able to work on my blog code using myÂ net-book which is currently running Ubuntu (10.04 Lucid Lynx), so I need to get Apache, MySql, and PHP working.\n<ul>\n	<li>Install Apache2 using \"sudo apt-get\"</li>\n</ul>\nSide note on UbuntuÂ terminal commands:\n<ul>\n	<li>the \"sudo\" command gives you root privileges to run a program</li>\n	<li>apt-get</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>References</h2>\n<a href=\"http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies\">http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies</a>','Developing my Blog','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision','','','2010-06-26 21:53:14','2010-06-26 20:53:14','',137,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/26/137-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(139,1,'2010-06-26 22:25:57','2010-06-26 21:25:57','<h2>Setting up LAMP on Ubuntu</h2>\nI want to be able to work on my blog code using myÂ net-book which is currently running Ubuntu (10.04 Lucid Lynx), so I need to get Apache, MySQL, and PHP working. It just takes a few simple steps.\n<ul>\n	<li>Install Apache2 using \"sudo apt-get\" (go to http://localhost/ to test)</li>\n	<li>Install PHP \"sudo apt-get install php5 libapache2-mod-php5\"</li>\n	<li>Test PHP by adding /var/www/testphp.php containing &lt;?php phpinfo(); ?&gt;</li>\n	<li>Install MySQL server \"sudo apt-get install mysql-server\"</li>\n	<li>Install MySQL Administrator (I used the Ubuntu Software Centre)</li>\n</ul>\nNext, create a new site configuration so that Apache can access my website files which are in /home/myusername/Desktop/myblog. This makes it easier to work with the website files as the default Apache site location has higher security restrictions. See the <a title=\"ApacheMySQLPHP Virtual Hosts\" href=\"https://help.ubuntu.com/community/ApacheMySQLPHP#Virtual Hosts\">Ubuntu Documentation</a> for instructions.\n\nSide note on UbuntuÂ terminal commands:\n<ul>\n	<li>the \"sudo\" command gives you root privileges to run a program</li>\n	<li>\"apt-get\" will download and install software packages</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>References</h2>\n<a href=\"http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies\">http://www.howtoforge.com/ubuntu_lamp_for_newbies</a>','Developing my Blog','','inherit','open','open','','137-revision-2','','','2010-06-26 22:25:57','2010-06-26 21:25:57','',137,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/26/137-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(140,1,'2010-04-21 11:47:27','2010-04-21 10:47:27','<span> </span>\r\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient value ContactDetails.Account</pre>\r\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\r\n\r\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.','NHibernate Errors','','inherit','open','open','','64-revision-4','','','2010-04-21 11:47:27','2010-04-21 10:47:27','',64,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(141,1,'2010-06-29 14:27:17','2010-06-29 13:27:17','Using AJAX to send a request to an MVC action protected with a <strong>ValidateAntiForgeryToken</strong> attribute requires that you send the token along with the request data. I\'ve simply copied the value from the hidden input element (generated using <strong>Html.AntiForgeryToken</strong> in the view). Here\'s the basic JavaScript:\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">function getAntiForgeryToken()\n{\n	var tokenElement = $(\'input[name=__RequestVerificationToken]\');\n	var token = $(tokenElement).val();\n	return token;\n}</pre>\nAnd the code for making the AJAX request uses the token in its request data:\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">$.post(\'/test.html\', {__RequestVerificationToken : getAntiForgeryToken() },\n	function (data) {\n		$(\"p.message\").html(data);\n	}, \'json\');</pre>\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span></strong>\n\n<a href=\"http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/\">http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/</a>\n\n<a href=\"http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx\">http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx</a>','ASP.NET MVC Anti Forgery Token and Ajax request','','inherit','open','open','','124-autosave','','','2010-06-29 14:27:17','2010-06-29 13:27:17','',124,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/29/124-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(142,1,'2010-02-27 21:50:32','2010-02-27 21:50:32','<p>I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Here\'s what I did:</p>\r\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\r\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\r\n','Wordpress in a lunch break','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision-5','','','2010-02-27 21:50:32','2010-02-27 21:50:32','',3,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/3-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(143,1,'2010-02-27 21:06:03','2010-02-27 21:06:03','This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\r\n\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\nvar aCookie = new HttpCookie(\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\")\r\n		{\r\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n		};\r\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">\r\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies[\"last_visited_global_homepage_url\"];\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that you can go back to the landing page and select a new country.','Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted','','inherit','open','open','','18-revision-8','','','2010-02-27 21:06:03','2010-02-27 21:06:03','',18,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/18-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(144,1,'2010-05-15 23:15:32','2010-05-15 22:15:32','<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property \"Property\" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>','EPiServer Snippets','A work in progress cheat sheet of EPiServer code snippets.','inherit','open','open','','89-revision-7','','','2010-05-15 23:15:32','2010-05-15 22:15:32','',89,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/89-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(146,1,'2010-06-02 13:56:16','2010-06-02 12:56:16','Using AJAX to send a request to an MVC action protected with a <strong>ValidateAntiForgeryToken</strong> attribute requires that you send the token along with the request data. I\'ve simply copied the value from the hidden input element (generated using <strong>Html.AntiForgeryToken</strong> in the view). Here\'s the basic JavaScript:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">function getAntiForgeryToken()\r\n{\r\n	var tokenElement = $(\'input[name=__RequestVerificationToken]\');\r\n	var token = $(tokenElement).val();\r\n	return token;\r\n}</pre>\r\nAnd the code for making the AJAX request uses the token in its request data:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:javascript\">$.post(\'/test.html\', {__RequestVerificationToken : getAntiForgeryToken() },\r\n	function (data) {\r\n		$(\"p.message\").html(data);\r\n	}, \'json\');</pre>\r\n<strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">References</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/\">http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/</a>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx\">http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx</a>','ASP.NET MVC Anti Forgery Token and Ajax request','','inherit','open','open','','124-revision-4','','','2010-06-02 13:56:16','2010-06-02 12:56:16','',124,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/02/124-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(148,1,'2010-05-05 11:42:32','2010-05-05 10:42:32','[caption id=\"\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Photo by geoftheref\"]<a href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/geoftheref/\"><img title=\"Baobab tree\" src=\"http://farm1.static.flickr.com/142/326561470_578a1d91d7_m_d.jpg\" alt=\"Photo by geoftheref\" width=\"240\" height=\"180\" /></a>[/caption]\r\n\r\nSo I need to start working on a redesign of a site that is live and is likely to have small maintenance jobs applied to it by our support team. I don\'t want to start changing the source of the trunk because my changes might get deployed by someone else half way through.\r\n\r\n<strong>Ths solution: branching</strong>\r\n\r\nI can create a branch of the code and work on this without affecting anyone else. And I can reintegrate my changes when they go live.\r\n\r\nFirst make sure you have the <a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/svn.tour.importing.html#svn.tour.importing.layout\" target=\"_self\">recommended repository layout</a> created. Use the Tortroise SVN repository browser tool to check.\r\n\r\nWhen you make a branch all you are doing is making a copy. You could use the <em><strong>svn copy</strong></em> command to copy the trunk to a new branch. (Subversion makes cheap copies - the duplicate is just a link to the original,Â untilÂ one of them changes)\r\n\r\nTo create a branch using Tortoise SVN:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Inside the trunk folder, Right-click and select TortoiseSVN &gt; Branch/Tag</li>\r\n	<li>In theÂ dialogueÂ box check you are copying from the trunk folder url to a branch folder url</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThis will create a branch (copy) in the repository. Now you need to check it out. You can either <strong><em>switch</em></strong> your working copy to the branch, or copy your working copy to a new folder and <strong><em>switch</em></strong> to the branch.\r\n\r\n<strong>Keep in sync</strong>\r\n\r\nRemember to keep your branch in sync with the trunk, if the trunk is being actively changed it could become so different from your trunk that it\'s impossible to reintegrate. Use <strong><em>merge</em><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\">, right-click, TortoiseSVN &gt; Merge.</span></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>References:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html\">http://svnbook.red-bean.com/en/1.5/index.html</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn\">http://stackoverflow.com/questions/1461922/what-is-the-simplest-way-to-do-branching-and-merging-using-tortoise-svn</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB\">http://docs.google.com/present/view?id=0AQAmNhjMdXXXZGdjdGJqeGhfNTBkcjcyd3pmbg&amp;hl=en_GB</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>\r\n</strong>','Branching with Tortoise SVN','','inherit','open','open','','31-revision-5','','','2010-05-05 11:42:32','2010-05-05 10:42:32','',31,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/05/31-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(149,1,'2010-07-09 22:36:13','2010-07-09 21:36:13','I want to create a new EPiServer project to develop in Visual Studio, what are my options?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use the Deployment Center to create a new site (with or without public templates)</li>\r\n	<li>Use the Visual Studio integration tools (Visual Studio Tools for EPiServer)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nI\'m going to note down the steps to creating a new  EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tool. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error<strong> \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\"</strong> which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a user</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\n<strong>Useful resources:</strong>\r\n\r\nEPiServer SDK:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>\r\n\r\nFrederik Vig, using the public templates site as a base for and EPiServer project:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/\">http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/</a>','How to create a new EPiServer 6 site in Visual Studio','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','publish','open','open','','creating-an-episerver-6-site','','','2010-08-28 21:58:57','2010-08-28 20:58:57','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=149',0,'post','',1),(150,1,'2010-07-09 21:43:54','2010-07-09 20:43:54','These are the steps Â to create a new EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tools. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at EPiServer Labs.','Creating an EPiServer 6 Site','','inherit','open','open','','149-revision','','','2010-07-09 21:43:54','2010-07-09 20:43:54','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/09/149-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(151,1,'2010-07-09 21:49:48','2010-07-09 20:49:48','','EPiServer6-VS2010-integration','','inherit','open','open','','episerver6-vs2010-integration','','','2010-07-09 21:49:48','2010-07-09 20:49:48','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(152,1,'2010-07-09 21:44:25','2010-07-09 20:44:25','These are the steps Â to create a new EP