','open','','170-revision-8','','','2010-08-22 08:34:23','2010-08-22 07:34:23','',170,'http://localhost/jsewell_mywordpressblog/index.php/2010/08/22/170-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(195,1,'2010-08-22 08:43:15','2010-08-22 07:43:15','The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\r\n\r\nI\'m going to create a css drop-down menu showing 2 levels of pages. This is the code for the PageTree control:\r\n<pre class=\"brush: xhtml\">\r\n&lt;EPiServer:PageTree ShowRootPage=\"false\" PageLink=\"&lt;%#PageReference.StartPage %&gt;\" NumberOfLevels=\"2\" ExpandAll=\"true\" runat=\"server\" ID=\"PrimaryNavigation\"&gt;\r\n	&lt;IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;EPiServer:Property ID=\"Property1\" PropertyName=\"PageLink\" runat=\"server\" /&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n&lt;/EPiServer:PageTree&gt;\r\n</pre>\r\nNote the properties in the parent element - ShowRootPage (whether to show the start page), PageLink (the starting page for the menu), ExpandAll (renders a menu item for every page), NumberOfLevels (the number of levels to render out).\r\n\r\nI\'ve put this on the start page template of my EPiServer site as it\'s just an exercise. Ideally it would be contained in an ascx user control that would be referenced from the master page of the site. So this renders all the markup I need for my menu, it\'s simply HTML lists.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-174\" title=\"primary-navigation-lists\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-lists-600x366.jpg\" alt=\"The primary navigation is rendered as a HTML lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"366\" />\r\n\r\nFirebug shows the HTML lists rendered by the PageTree control and my templates.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-175\" title=\"primary-nav-markup-in-firebug\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-nav-markup-in-firebug-600x430.jpg\" alt=\"Firebug shows the markup of the navigation lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"430\" />\r\n\r\nNext it\'s just a matter of applying some css style to get the menu looking and behaving a bit more like a menu. I\'ve wrapped the PageTree control with a div element with an id of \"priary-nav\" so I can target it with css rules.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:css\">div#primary-nav ul\r\n{\r\n	list-style-image: none;\r\n	list-style-position: outside;\r\n	list-style-type: none;\r\n	margin: 0;\r\n	padding: 0;\r\n	text-align:center;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li\r\n	{\r\n		float: left;\r\n		background-color: #ccc;\r\n		width:100px;\r\n		text-align:center;\r\n	}\r\n		div#primary-nav li a\r\n		{\r\n			padding:5px;\r\n			display:block;\r\n		}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li ul\r\n{\r\n	width:100px;\r\n	position: absolute;\r\n	left: -999em;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li ul li\r\n	{\r\n		background-color: #eee;\r\n	}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li:hover ul\r\n{\r\n	left: auto;\r\n}</pre>\r\nAnd with style applied the menu looks like this:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-176\" title=\"primary-navigation-with-css\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-with-css.jpg\" alt=\"The navigation menu with css rules applied\" width=\"369\" height=\"207\" />\r\n\r\nBuilding on this example should enable me to quickly build drop-down menus for a number of scenarios - there are a lot more properties and templates of the PageTree control to explore, and understanding the basics is the first step to building more complex navigation to fit the requirements of a specific site.\r\n\r\nUseful links:\r\n\r\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/','EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation','','inherit','open','open','','170-revision-9','','','2010-08-22 08:43:15','2010-08-22 07:43:15','',170,'http://localhost/jsewell_mywordpressblog/index.php/2010/08/22/170-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(197,1,'2010-08-22 08:47:52','2010-08-22 07:47:52','The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\r\n<pre class=\"brush: js\">function foo()\r\n{\r\n}</pre>\r\nI\'m going to create a css drop-down menu showing 2 levels of pages. This is the code for the PageTree control:\r\n<pre class=\"brush: xhtml\">&lt;EPiServer:PageTree ShowRootPage=\"false\" PageLink=\"&lt;%#PageReference.StartPage %&gt;\" NumberOfLevels=\"2\" ExpandAll=\"true\" runat=\"server\" ID=\"PrimaryNavigation\"&gt;\r\n	&lt;IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/IndentTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;EPiServer:Property ID=\"Property1\" PropertyName=\"PageLink\" runat=\"server\" /&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/li&gt;\r\n	&lt;/ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\r\n	&lt;UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n	&lt;/UnindentTemplate&gt;\r\n&lt;/EPiServer:PageTree&gt;</pre>\r\nNote the properties in the parent element - ShowRootPage (whether to show the start page), PageLink (the starting page for the menu), ExpandAll (renders a menu item for every page), NumberOfLevels (the number of levels to render out).\r\n\r\nI\'ve put this on the start page template of my EPiServer site as it\'s just an exercise. Ideally it would be contained in an ascx user control that would be referenced from the master page of the site. So this renders all the markup I need for my menu, it\'s simply HTML lists.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-174\" title=\"primary-navigation-lists\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-lists-600x366.jpg\" alt=\"The primary navigation is rendered as a HTML lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"366\" />\r\n\r\nFirebug shows the HTML lists rendered by the PageTree control and my templates.\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-175\" title=\"primary-nav-markup-in-firebug\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-nav-markup-in-firebug-600x430.jpg\" alt=\"Firebug shows the markup of the navigation lists\" width=\"600\" height=\"430\" />\r\n\r\nNext it\'s just a matter of applying some css style to get the menu looking and behaving a bit more like a menu. I\'ve wrapped the PageTree control with a div element with an id of \"priary-nav\" so I can target it with css rules.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:css\">div#primary-nav ul\r\n{\r\n	list-style-image: none;\r\n	list-style-position: outside;\r\n	list-style-type: none;\r\n	margin: 0;\r\n	padding: 0;\r\n	text-align:center;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li\r\n	{\r\n		float: left;\r\n		background-color: #ccc;\r\n		width:100px;\r\n		text-align:center;\r\n	}\r\n		div#primary-nav li a\r\n		{\r\n			padding:5px;\r\n			display:block;\r\n		}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li ul\r\n{\r\n	width:100px;\r\n	position: absolute;\r\n	left: -999em;\r\n}\r\n	div#primary-nav li ul li\r\n	{\r\n		background-color: #eee;\r\n	}\r\n\r\ndiv#primary-nav li:hover ul\r\n{\r\n	left: auto;\r\n}</pre>\r\nAnd with style applied the menu looks like this:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-176\" title=\"primary-navigation-with-css\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-with-css.jpg\" alt=\"The navigation menu with css rules applied\" width=\"369\" height=\"207\" />\r\n\r\nBuilding on this example should enable me to quickly build drop-down menus for a number of scenarios - there are a lot more properties and templates of the PageTree control to explore, and understanding the basics is the first step to building more complex navigation to fit the requirements of a specific site.\r\n\r\nUseful links:\r\n\r\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/','EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation','','inherit','open','open','','170-revision-10','','','2010-08-22 08:47:52','2010-08-22 07:47:52','',170,'http://localhost/jsewell_mywordpressblog/index.php/2010/08/22/170-revision-10/',0,'revision','',0),(199,1,'2010-07-10 22:23:31','2010-07-10 21:23:31','These are the steps Â to create a new EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tools. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\" which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\nUseful resources:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>','Creating an EPiServer 6 Site','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-12','','','2010-07-10 22:23:31','2010-07-10 21:23:31','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/10/149-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(200,1,'2010-08-28 20:54:39','2010-08-28 19:54:39','These are the steps to create a new (without any sample templates) EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tool. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error<strong> \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\"</strong> which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a user</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\nUseful resources:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>','How to create a new EPiServer 6 site in Visual Studio','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-13','','','2010-08-28 20:54:39','2010-08-28 19:54:39','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/28/149-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(201,1,'2010-08-28 21:08:31','2010-08-28 20:08:31','These are the steps to create a new (without any sample templates) EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tool. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error<strong> \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\"</strong> which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a user</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\n<strong>Useful resources:</strong>\r\n\r\nEPiServer SDK:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>\r\n\r\nFrederik Vig, using the public templates site as a base for and EPiServer project:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/\">http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/</a>','How to create a new EPiServer 6 site in Visual Studio','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-14','','','2010-08-28 21:08:31','2010-08-28 20:08:31','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/28/149-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(202,1,'2010-08-28 21:16:07','2010-08-28 20:16:07','I want to create a new EPiServer project to develop in Visual Studio, what are my options?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use the Deployment Center to create a new site (with or without public templates)</li>\r\n	<li>Use the Visual Studio integration tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nI\'m going to note down the steps to creating a new  EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tool. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error<strong> \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\"</strong> which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a user</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\n<strong>Useful resources:</strong>\r\n\r\nEPiServer SDK:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>\r\n\r\nFrederik Vig, using the public templates site as a base for and EPiServer project:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/\">http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/</a>','How to create a new EPiServer 6 site in Visual Studio','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-15','','','2010-08-28 21:16:07','2010-08-28 20:16:07','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/28/149-revision-15/',0,'revision','',0),(203,1,'2010-08-28 21:16:38','2010-08-28 20:16:38','I want to create a new EPiServer project to develop in Visual Studio, what are my options?\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Use the Deployment Center to create a new site (with or without public templates)</li>\r\n	<li>Use the Visual Studio integration tool</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nI\'m going to note down the steps to creating a new  EPiServer 6 site using the Visual Studio integration tool. First you need to install the integration tools, they come as part of the EPiServer installation files. Install them by running EPiServerVsIntegration.msi. This installer doesn\'t support Visual Studio 2010 but you can still use the ntegration tools by following these instructions at <a title=\"Getting the Visual Studio integration built for VS 2005 worging in VS 2008\" href=\"http://labs.episerver.com/en/Blogs/Fredrik-Tjarnberg/Dates/2009/5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2-in-Visual-Studio-2010/\">EPiServer Labs</a>.\r\n\r\nOnce you have the integration tools installed you should be able to create a new EPiServer 6 project.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"EPiServer6-VS2010-integration\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/EPiServer6-VS2010-integration-1024x577.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"577\" />\r\n\r\nThis should create a new web application with a few core files and a database.\r\n\r\n<img title=\"a-new-episerver6-application\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-application.jpg\" alt=\"The files in the new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"348\" height=\"402\" />\r\nOnce the project is created, if I hit F5 to launch the application, in Chrome I get an error<strong> \"Error 312 (net::ERR_UNSAFE_PORT): Unknown error.\"</strong> which I assume is because Chrome doesn\'t trust port 6666. Looking at the website in Firefox, however gives me the EPiServer 6 login screen.\r\n\r\n<strong>Create a user</strong>\r\n\r\nNow I need to create a new user, so in Visual Studio, go to Project &gt; ASP.NET Configuration in the menu.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Select the Provider tab. Choose \"Select a different provider for each feature (advanced)\", and select \"SqlServerRoleProvider\" (you can use any)</li>\r\n	<li>Next, go to the \"Security\" tab and create a role called \"WebAdmins\" and create a user in that role too</li>\r\n	<li>Now head back to the login screen and login with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said \"Root folder\" with no menus at the top or left, I had to click \"My Settings\" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with. (Note that some time during this process I added licence file to the project... a requested a demo licence from <a href=\"http://license.episerver.com/\">http://license.episerver.com/</a>)\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-159\" title=\"a-new-episerver6-site\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg\" alt=\"The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site\" width=\"600\" height=\"357\" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I\'ve done this in Admin Mode on the \"Set access rights\" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-164\" title=\"episerver6-set-access-rights\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg\" alt=\"The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen\" width=\"600\" height=\"303\" />\r\n\r\nNext, I need a home page (or start page in EPiServer terminology), so I\'ve added a new template file name StartPage.aspx using the EPiServer Visual Studio template, and clicked \"no\" when prompted to register a PageType. This adds an aspx file to my project with some markup already in it, but commented out (and the page inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). I\'m not using a master page here so I uncomment the markup and add a paragraph of text:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:html\">&lt;p&gt;Hello this is my start page.&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\nCreate a page type for this template in admin mode.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-167\" title=\"add-a-new-page-type\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/add-a-new-page-type1-600x316.jpg\" alt=\"The admin moe screen for adding a new page type\" width=\"600\" height=\"316\" />\r\n\r\nMake sure you get the file name correct, the project has a virtual path set up which you\'ll need to put in, or use the tilde \"~/StartPage.aspx\", if you get the path wrong you\'ll see an error \"The virtual path \'/StartPage.aspx\' maps to another application, which is not allowed.\" (Which I got the first time round...)\r\n\r\nNext, I add a new Start Page to the page tree and publish it.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-medium wp-image-168\" title=\"home-page\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/home-page-600x270.jpg\" alt=\"The new home page shows in the page tree\" width=\"600\" height=\"270\" />\r\n\r\nNext I need to configure EPiServer to use this new page as the start page. If you hover over it you can see the page id is 5. You need to open EPiServer.config and set \"pageStartId\" to 5. Now when I go to the root of my site (http://localhost:6666/EPiServer1/) I get my Home page. (Note you will need to reload the AppDomain to get the new config changes - saving the web.config will do this)\r\n\r\n<strong>Useful resources:</strong>\r\n\r\nEPiServer SDK:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm\">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>\r\n\r\nFrederik Vig, using the public templates site as a base for and EPiServer project:\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/\">http://www.frederikvig.com/2009/12/part-1-setting-up-the-development-environment-create-an-episerver-site-from-scratch/</a>','How to create a new EPiServer 6 site in Visual Studio','If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I\'ve noted down the steps here.','inherit','open','open','','149-revision-16','','','2010-08-28 21:16:38','2010-08-28 20:16:38','',149,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/28/149-revision-16/',0,'revision','',0),(204,1,'2010-09-07 16:59:39','2010-09-07 15:59:39','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\r\n\r\nIn order to maintain maximum control over what is installed on the web server you might try to install the service using the <strong>installutil </strong>program. I tried this approach, I copied the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\" and ran the command:\r\n\r\n<strong>installutil EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe</strong>\r\n\r\nBut this doesn\'t work and you\'ll get an error:\r\n\r\n<strong>No public installers with the RunInstallerAttribute.Yes attribute could be found in the D:\\sites\\mysite\\EPiServerSchedulerService5.2.375.236\\EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe assembly.</strong>\r\n\r\nThe scheduler service is not designed to be manually installed like this. As such your only option is to install it using <strong>EPiServerShared.msi</strong> from the EPiServer CMS installation files (available on <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Download/Categories/Products/EPiServer-CMS/\">EPiServer World</a>). This will install and start 3 services and won\'t require you to restart the machine:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>EPiServer Scheduler Service</li>\r\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Log Service</li>\r\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Indexing Service</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIt\'s not an ideal solution if you like to maintain absolute control over what is installed on the web server, but it\'s a quick and easy install that does work.','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?','publish','open','open','','installing-the-episerver-scheduler-service','','','2011-02-04 10:03:39','2011-02-04 10:03:39','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=204',0,'post','',0),(205,1,'2010-09-07 12:27:56','2010-09-07 11:27:56','','EPiServer-scheduler-service','','inherit','open','open','','episerver-scheduler-service','','','2010-09-07 12:27:56','2010-09-07 11:27:56','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(206,1,'2010-09-07 12:33:15','2010-09-07 11:33:15','We\'ve just launched a new site and need to get the scheduler service up and running.  \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','','inherit','open','open','','204-revision','','','2010-09-07 12:33:15','2010-09-07 11:33:15','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/07/204-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(207,1,'2010-09-07 12:37:51','2010-09-07 11:37:51','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed on the web server in question. We\'ve just launched a new site and need to get the scheduler service up and running on this server.  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nThese are the steps I\'m going to follow:\n<ol>\n	<li>Install EPiServer (in this case version</li>\n</ol>','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','','inherit','open','open','','204-revision-2','','','2010-09-07 12:37:51','2010-09-07 11:37:51','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/07/204-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(208,1,'2010-09-07 12:50:30','2010-09-07 11:50:30','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed on the web server in question. We\'ve just launched a new site and need to get the scheduler service up and running on this server.  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nThese are the steps I\'m going to follow:\n<ol>\n	<li>Install the version of EPiServer on you development machine and copy the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\"</li>\n	<li>FTP the scheduler service files to the web server</li>\n	<li>Install the service using <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/50614e95(VS.80).aspx\">installutil</a></li>\n	<li><a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/50614e95(VS.80).aspx\"></a></li>\n</ol>\nOpen a command prompt and change directory to the directory containing the service files and run the command:\n\nC:\\WINDOWS\\Microsoft.NET\\Framework64\\v2.0.50727\\installutil','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','','inherit','open','open','','204-revision-3','','','2010-09-07 12:50:30','2010-09-07 11:50:30','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/07/204-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(209,1,'2010-09-07 13:59:30','2010-09-07 12:59:30','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed on the web server in question. We\'ve just launched a new site and need to get the scheduler service up and running on this server.  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nThese are the steps I\'m going to follow:\n<ol>\n	<li>Install the version of EPiServer on you development machine and copy the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\"</li>\n	<li>FTP the scheduler service files to the web server</li>\n	<li>Install the service using <a href=\"http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/50614e95(VS.80).aspx\">installutil</a> (run at command prompt: C:\\WINDOWS\\Microsoft.NET\\Framework64\\v2.0.50727\\installutil D:\\sites\\EPiServerSchedulerService\\EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe)</li>\n</ol>','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','','inherit','open','open','','204-revision-4','','','2010-09-07 13:59:30','2010-09-07 12:59:30','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/07/204-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(211,1,'2010-09-07 16:59:38','2010-09-07 15:59:38','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nIn order to maintain maximum control over what is installed on the web server you might try to install the service using the <strong>installutil </strong>program. I tried this approach, I copied the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\" and ran the command:\n\n<strong>installutil EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe</strong>\n\nBut this doesn\'t work and you\'ll get an error:\n\n<strong>No public installers with the RunInstallerAttribute.Yes attribute could be found in the D:\\sites\\jisc-collections.ac.uk\\EPiServerSchedulerService5.2.375.236\\EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe assembly.</strong>\n\nThe scheduler service is not designed to be manually installed like this. As such your only option is to install it using <strong>EPiServerShared.msi</strong> from the EPiServer CMS installation files (available on <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Download/Categories/Products/EPiServer-CMS/\">EPiServer World</a>). This will install and start 3 services and won\'t require you to restart the machine:\n<ul>\n	<li>EPiServer Scheduler Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Log Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Indexing Service</li>\n</ul>\nIt\'s not an ideal solution if you like to maintain absolute control over what is installed on the web server, but it\'s a quick and easy install that does work.','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?','inherit','open','open','','204-revision-5','','','2010-09-07 16:59:38','2010-09-07 15:59:38','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/07/204-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(212,1,'2010-09-08 22:23:16','2010-09-08 21:23:16','<div>\r\n\r\nI came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file.\r\n\r\nIn version 4 I had an \"upload\" virtual path which was used for page files and global uploads. As part of the upgrade I separated the page files into their own folder with their own virtual path (/pages/). This creates a problem because all the links in content still point at /upload/ for page files. So you need to add:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;unifiedFileSystem&gt;\r\n	&lt;mappings&gt;\r\n		&lt;map fromPath=\"/upload\" toPath=\"/pages\" type=\"EPiServer.FileSystem.Mapping.PageDirectoryMapping,EPiServer\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nMore info here: <a href=\"../../../en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites</a>\r\n\r\nThen during the upgrade that mapping gets converted to something like this:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;add toPath=\"~/pages/\" fromPath=\"~/upload/\" name=\"Mapping0\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathPageMappingProvider,EPiServer.Legacy4\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nSo the VirtualPahPageMappingProvider is mapping requests for the path /upload/ to path /pages/, it should be last in the list of providers in the configuration if you have another provider handling the /upload/ path.\r\n\r\n</div>','Meeting the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider','I came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file...','publish','open','open','','meeting-the-virtualpathpagemappingprovider','','','2010-09-09 08:53:08','2010-09-09 07:53:08','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=212',0,'post','',0),(213,1,'2010-09-08 22:23:03','2010-09-08 21:23:03','<div>\n\nI came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file.\n\nIn version 4 I had an \"upload\" virtual path which was used for page files and global uploads. As part of the upgrade I separated the page files into their own folder with their own virtual path (/pages/). This creates a problem because all the links in content still point at /upload/ for page files. So you need to add:\n<pre>&lt;unifiedFileSystem&gt;\n	&lt;mappings&gt;\n		&lt;map fromPath=\"/upload\" toPath=\"/pages\" type=\"EPiServer.FileSystem.Mapping.PageDirectoryMapping,EPiServer\" /&gt;</pre>\nMore info here: <a href=\"../../../en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites</a>\n\nThen during the upgrade that mapping gets converted to something like this:\n<pre>&lt;add toPath=\"~/pages/\" fromPath=\"~/upload/\" name=\"Mapping0\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathPageMappingProvider,EPiServer.Legacy4\" /&gt;</pre>\nSo the VirtualPahPageMappingProvider is mapping requests for the path /upload/ to path /pages/, it should be last in the list of providers in the configuration if you have another provider handling the /upload/ path.\n\n</div>','Meeting the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider','','inherit','open','open','','212-revision','','','2010-09-08 22:23:03','2010-09-08 21:23:03','',212,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/08/212-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(214,1,'2010-09-08 22:23:16','2010-09-08 21:23:16','<div>\r\n\r\nI came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file.\r\n\r\nIn version 4 I had an \"upload\" virtual path which was used for page files and global uploads. As part of the upgrade I separated the page files into their own folder with their own virtual path (/pages/). This creates a problem because all the links in content still point at /upload/ for page files. So you need to add:\r\n<pre>&lt;unifiedFileSystem&gt;\r\n	&lt;mappings&gt;\r\n		&lt;map fromPath=\"/upload\" toPath=\"/pages\" type=\"EPiServer.FileSystem.Mapping.PageDirectoryMapping,EPiServer\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nMore info here: <a href=\"../../../en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites</a>\r\n\r\nThen during the upgrade that mapping gets converted to something like this:\r\n<pre>&lt;add toPath=\"~/pages/\" fromPath=\"~/upload/\" name=\"Mapping0\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathPageMappingProvider,EPiServer.Legacy4\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nSo the VirtualPahPageMappingProvider is mapping requests for the path /upload/ to path /pages/, it should be last in the list of providers in the configuration if you have another provider handling the /upload/ path.\r\n\r\n</div>','Meeting the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider','','inherit','open','open','','212-revision-2','','','2010-09-08 22:23:16','2010-09-08 21:23:16','',212,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/08/212-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(215,1,'2010-09-08 22:25:05','2010-09-08 21:25:05','<div>\r\n\r\nI came across this when I did an upgrade from EPiServer 4 to 5, the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider showed up in the config file.\r\n\r\nIn version 4 I had an \"upload\" virtual path which was used for page files and global uploads. As part of the upgrade I separated the page files into their own folder with their own virtual path (/pages/). This creates a problem because all the links in content still point at /upload/ for page files. So you need to add:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;unifiedFileSystem&gt;\r\n	&lt;mappings&gt;\r\n		&lt;map fromPath=\"/upload\" toPath=\"/pages\" type=\"EPiServer.FileSystem.Mapping.PageDirectoryMapping,EPiServer\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nMore info here: <a href=\"../../../en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites\">http://world.episerver.com/en/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-5/EPiServer-CMS-5-R2/EPiServer-CMS-Migration-Tool-11/#Prerequisites</a>\r\n\r\nThen during the upgrade that mapping gets converted to something like this:\r\n<pre class=\"brush:xml\">&lt;add toPath=\"~/pages/\" fromPath=\"~/upload/\" name=\"Mapping0\" type=\"EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathPageMappingProvider,EPiServer.Legacy4\" /&gt;</pre>\r\nSo the VirtualPahPageMappingProvider is mapping requests for the path /upload/ to path /pages/, it should be last in the list of providers in the configuration if you have another provider handling the /upload/ path.\r\n\r\n</div>','Meeting the VirtualPathPageMappingProvider','','inherit','open','open','','212-revision-3','','','2010-09-08 22:25:05','2010-09-08 21:25:05','',212,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/08/212-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(216,1,'2010-09-09 08:54:16','2010-09-09 07:54:16','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?  Any Admin Mode page that relies on the scheduler service is showing a warning: \"The EPiServer Scheduler Service does not  appear to be active, it may have been stopped.\"\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-205\" title=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/EPiServer-scheduler-service.jpg\" alt=\"EPiServer-scheduler-service\" width=\"770\" height=\"134\" />\n\nIn order to maintain maximum control over what is installed on the web server you might try to install the service using the <strong>installutil </strong>program. I tried this approach, I copied the EPiServer scheduler service files from \"C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\Shared\\Services\\Scheduler Service\" and ran the command:\n\n<strong>installutil EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe</strong>\n\nBut this doesn\'t work and you\'ll get an error:\n\n<strong>No public installers with the RunInstallerAttribute.Yes attribute could be found in the D:\\sites\\jisc-collections.ac.uk\\EPiServerSchedulerService5.2.375.236\\EPiServer.SchedulerSvc.exe assembly.</strong>\n\nThe scheduler service is not designed to be manually installed like this. As such your only option is to install it using <strong>EPiServerShared.msi</strong> from the EPiServer CMS installation files (available on <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Download/Categories/Products/EPiServer-CMS/\">EPiServer World</a>). This will install and start 3 services and won\'t require you to restart the machine:\n<ul>\n	<li>EPiServer Scheduler Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Log Service</li>\n	<li>EPiServer CMS Indexing Service</li>\n</ul>\nIt\'s not an ideal solution if you like to maintain absolute control over what is installed on the web server, but it\'s a quick and easy install that does work.','Installing the EPiServer Scheduler Service','We have our own (XCopy type) deployment process and don\'t use the EPiServer Deployment Centre or any of the installers on our web servers, as a result the scheduler service is not installed. So how do you get the EPiServer Scheduler Service installed on the web server?','inherit','open','open','','204-autosave','','','2010-09-09 08:54:16','2010-09-09 07:54:16','',204,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/09/204-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(217,1,'2010-08-25 14:01:28','2010-08-25 13:01:28','PageReference has an ID property, PageData does not\n\nPageReference.StartPage gets you the page refrence of the start page (PageReference.RootPage exists too)\n\nGlobal.UrlRewriteProvider.ConvertToExternal - get the friendly URL of a page (there is a method ConvertToInternal too)\n\nExample:\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">UrlBuilder urlBuilder = new UrlBuilder(EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.SiteUrl);</div>\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">Global.UrlRewriteProvider.ConvertToExternal(urlBuilderÂ , page.PageLink, System.Text.UTF8Encoding.UTF8);</div>\n<div>var friendlyUrl -=Â urlBuilder.ToString();</div>','EPiServer snippets','','inherit','open','open','','179-revision-8','','','2010-08-25 14:01:28','2010-08-25 13:01:28','',179,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/25/179-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(218,1,'2010-09-23 15:22:06','2010-09-23 14:22:06','EPiServer Dynamic properties are very useful and it\'s tempting to make generous use of them.\r\n\r\nI\'m working on a feature and trying to decide if I should use dynamic properties or a property on the page type. I\'ve decided to avoid dynamic properties in this case because dynamic properties apply to ALL pages, but they are not necessarily used by all pages.\r\n\r\nCreating a dynamic property for something that is only used by a few page types causes confusion because it can be set on any of the ancestors of a pages, but may only be used by one or a few pages. In cases like this it\'s better to keep the property close to the items it affects.','What\'s wrong with EPiServer Dynamic Properties','A quick note on why dynamic properties are often a bad idea.','publish','open','open','','whats-wrong-with-episerver-dynamic-properties','','','2010-10-26 13:38:11','2010-10-26 12:38:11','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=218',0,'post','',0),(219,1,'2010-09-23 15:21:16','2010-09-23 14:21:16','EPiServer Dynamic properties are very useful and it\'s tempting to make generous use of them.\n\nI\'m working on a feature and trying to decide if I should use dynamic properties or a property on the page type. I\'ve decided to avoid dynamic properties in this case because dynamic properties apply to ALL pages, but they are not necessarily used by all pages.\n\nCreating a dynamic property for something that is only used by a few page types causes confusion because it can be set on any of the ancestors of a pages, but may only be used by one or a few pages. In cases like this it\'s better to keep the property close to the object it affects.','What\'s wrong with EPiServer Dynamic Properties','','inherit','open','open','','218-revision','','','2010-09-23 15:21:16','2010-09-23 14:21:16','',218,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/23/218-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(221,1,'2010-09-28 23:09:57','2010-09-28 22:09:57','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>. Why Git? Well the obvious benefits are speed in downloading from a remote repository, and there are no .svn folders in all the project folders. And it\'s a distributed system that gives you a local repository to work with, so if the remote server is unavailable (or you don\'t have internet access) you can still use your local repository.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>What are public/private keys?</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','publish','open','open','','git-and-the-secure-shell-ssh','','','2010-10-27 22:55:27','2010-10-27 21:55:27','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=221',0,'post','',0),(222,1,'2010-09-28 23:08:52','2010-09-28 22:08:52','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>.\n\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\n<ul>\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\n</ul>\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\n\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\n\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (As far as','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-revision','','','2010-09-28 23:08:52','2010-09-28 22:08:52','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/28/221-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(223,1,'2010-10-02 11:22:19','2010-10-02 10:22:19','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>. Why Git? Well the obvious benefits are speed in downloading from a remote repository, and there are no .svn folders in all the project folders. And it\'s a distributed system that gives you a local repository to work with, so if the remote server is unavailable (or you don\'t have internet access) you can still use your local repository.\n\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\n<ul>\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\n</ul>\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\n\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\n\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-autosave','','','2010-10-02 11:22:19','2010-10-02 10:22:19','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/28/221-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(224,1,'2010-09-28 23:09:57','2010-09-28 22:09:57','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-revision-2','','','2010-09-28 23:09:57','2010-09-28 22:09:57','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/28/221-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(225,1,'2010-09-28 23:21:03','2010-09-28 22:21:03','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-revision-3','','','2010-09-28 23:21:03','2010-09-28 22:21:03','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/09/28/221-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(226,1,'2010-10-25 16:19:21','2010-10-25 15:19:21','Today I had a task to remove the \"Heading 1\" and \"Heading 2\" options from the format drop-down in the EPiServer 6 TinyMCE editor. This is how I did it.\r\n\r\nTinyMCE has a <a title=\"TinyMCE Configuration\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Configuration\">whole lot of configuration options</a> for customising it to your needs. However, in EPiServer 6 it\'s not a matter of writing a JavaScript initialisation snippet and passing in these configuration settings, instead you need to add the configuration options as a plugin.\r\n<blockquote>In EPiServer CMS, we have two plug-in attributes called “TinyMCEPluginButton” and “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” which contains data EPiServer CMS needs to correctly show the plug-in in edit and admin mode. Which attribute to use depends on what type of plug-in you are creating. If the plug-in has one or more buttons the “TinyMCEPluginButton” should be used, if not use “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” attribute. <a title=\"TinyMCE Developers Guide on EPiServer World\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">TinyMCE Developers Guide</a></blockquote>\r\nSo I created a new class with a plugin attribute and passed in the TinyMCE configuration options to the EditorInitConfigurationOptions property.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[TinyMCEPluginNonVisual(AlwaysEnabled = true,\r\n	PlugInName = \"CustomTinyMceSettings\",\r\n	EditorInitConfigurationOptions =\r\n		@\"{\r\n			theme_advanced_blockformats : \'p,h3,h4,h5,h6\'\r\n		}\"\r\n	)]\r\npublic class CustomTinyMceSettings\r\n{\r\n}</pre>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/10/how-to-add-support-for-iframes-and-other-elements-to-tinymce-in-episerver-cms/\">Frederik Vig</a>, <a href=\"http://www.kloojed.com/2010/05/customize-the-tiny-mce-editor-options-in-episerver-cms-6\">Marcus Lindblom</a>, and <a href=\"http://krompaco.nu/alter-default-initoptions-for-tinymce-in-episerver-6/\">Johan Kronberg</a> have covered this in blog posts.\r\n\r\nAlso check out the <a title=\"TinyMCE documentation\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Installation\">TinyMCE </a>and <a title=\"EPiServer docs\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">EPiServer </a>documentation.','Remove h1 from EPiServer 6 TinyMCE','','publish','open','open','','remove-h1-from-episerver-6-tinymce','','\nhttp://krompaco.nu/alter-default-initoptions-for-tinymce-in-episerver-6/','2010-10-26 13:35:27','2010-10-26 12:35:27','',0,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=226',0,'post','',1),(227,1,'2010-10-25 16:18:27','2010-10-25 15:18:27','Today I had a task to remove the \"Heading 1\" and \"Heading 2\" options from the format drop-down in the EPiServer 6 TinyMCE editor. This is how I did it.\n\nTinyMCE has a <a title=\"TinyMCE Configuration\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Configuration\">whole lot of configuration options</a> for customising it to your needs. However, in EPiServer 6 it\'s not a matter of writing a JavaScript initialisation snippet and passing in these configuration settings, instead you need to add the configuration options as a plugin.\n<blockquote>In EPiServer CMS, we have two plug-in attributes called “TinyMCEPluginButton” and “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” which contains data EPiServer CMS needs to correctly show the plug-in in edit and admin mode. Which attribute to use depends on what type of plug-in you are creating. If the plug-in has one or more buttons the “TinyMCEPluginButton” should be used, if not use “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” attribute. <a title=\"TinyMCE Developers Guide on EPiServer World\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">TinyMCE Developers Guide</a></blockquote>\nSo I created a new class with a plugin attribute and passed in the TinyMCE configuration options to the EditorInitConfigurationOptions property.\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[TinyMCEPluginNonVisual(AlwaysEnabled = true,\n	PlugInName = \"CustomTinyMceSettings\",\n	EditorInitConfigurationOptions =\n		@\"{\n			theme_advanced_blockformats : \'p,h3,h4,h5,h6\'\n		}\"\n	)]\npublic class CustomTinyMceSettings\n{\n}</pre>\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/10/how-to-add-support-for-iframes-and-other-elements-to-tinymce-in-episerver-cms/\">Frederik Vig</a>, <a href=\"http://www.kloojed.com/2010/05/customize-the-tiny-mce-editor-options-in-episerver-cms-6\">Marcus Lindblom</a>, and <a href=\"http://krompaco.nu/alter-default-initoptions-for-tinymce-in-episerver-6/\">Johan Kronberg</a> have covered this in blog posts.\n\nTinyMCE is well documented','Remove h1 from EPiServer 6 TinyMCE','','inherit','open','open','','226-revision','','','2010-10-25 16:18:27','2010-10-25 15:18:27','',226,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/25/226-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(228,1,'2010-10-25 16:19:21','2010-10-25 15:19:21','Today I had a task to remove the \"Heading 1\" and \"Heading 2\" options from the format drop-down in the EPiServer 6 TinyMCE editor. This is how I did it.\r\n\r\nTinyMCE has a <a title=\"TinyMCE Configuration\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Configuration\">whole lot of configuration options</a> for customising it to your needs. However, in EPiServer 6 it\'s not a matter of writing a JavaScript initialisation snippet and passing in these configuration settings, instead you need to add the configuration options as a plugin.\r\n<blockquote>In EPiServer CMS, we have two plug-in attributes called “TinyMCEPluginButton” and “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” which contains data EPiServer CMS needs to correctly show the plug-in in edit and admin mode. Which attribute to use depends on what type of plug-in you are creating. If the plug-in has one or more buttons the “TinyMCEPluginButton” should be used, if not use “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” attribute. <a title=\"TinyMCE Developers Guide on EPiServer World\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">TinyMCE Developers Guide</a></blockquote>\r\nSo I created a new class with a plugin attribute and passed in the TinyMCE configuration options to the EditorInitConfigurationOptions property.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[TinyMCEPluginNonVisual(AlwaysEnabled = true,\r\n	PlugInName = \"CustomTinyMceSettings\",\r\n	EditorInitConfigurationOptions =\r\n		@\"{\r\n			theme_advanced_blockformats : \'p,h3,h4,h5,h6\'\r\n		}\"\r\n	)]\r\npublic class CustomTinyMceSettings\r\n{\r\n}</pre>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/10/how-to-add-support-for-iframes-and-other-elements-to-tinymce-in-episerver-cms/\">Frederik Vig</a>, <a href=\"http://www.kloojed.com/2010/05/customize-the-tiny-mce-editor-options-in-episerver-cms-6\">Marcus Lindblom</a>, and <a href=\"http://krompaco.nu/alter-default-initoptions-for-tinymce-in-episerver-6/\">Johan Kronberg</a> have covered this in blog posts.\r\n\r\nAlso check out the <a title=\"TinyMCE documentation\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Installation\">TinyMCE </a>and <a title=\"EPiServer docs\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">EPiServer </a>documentation.','Remove h1 from EPiServer 6 TinyMCE','','inherit','open','open','','226-revision-2','','','2010-10-25 16:19:21','2010-10-25 15:19:21','',226,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/25/226-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(229,1,'2010-10-25 16:20:01','2010-10-25 15:20:01','Today I had a task to remove the \"Heading 1\" and \"Heading 2\" options from the format drop-down in the EPiServer 6 TinyMCE editor. This is how I did it.\r\n\r\nTinyMCE has a <a title=\"TinyMCE Configuration\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Configuration\">whole lot of configuration options</a> for customising it to your needs. However, in EPiServer 6 it\'s not a matter of writing a JavaScript initialisation snippet and passing in these configuration settings, instead you need to add the configuration options as a plugin.\r\n<blockquote>In EPiServer CMS, we have two plug-in attributes called “TinyMCEPluginButton” and “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” which contains data EPiServer CMS needs to correctly show the plug-in in edit and admin mode. Which attribute to use depends on what type of plug-in you are creating. If the plug-in has one or more buttons the “TinyMCEPluginButton” should be used, if not use “TinyMCEPluginNonVisual” attribute. <a title=\"TinyMCE Developers Guide on EPiServer World\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">TinyMCE Developers Guide</a></blockquote>\r\nSo I created a new class with a plugin attribute and passed in the TinyMCE configuration options to the EditorInitConfigurationOptions property.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[TinyMCEPluginNonVisual(AlwaysEnabled = true,\r\n	PlugInName = \"CustomTinyMceSettings\",\r\n	EditorInitConfigurationOptions =\r\n		@\"{\r\n			theme_advanced_blockformats : \'p,h3,h4,h5,h6\'\r\n		}\"\r\n	)]\r\npublic class CustomTinyMceSettings\r\n{\r\n}</pre>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/10/how-to-add-support-for-iframes-and-other-elements-to-tinymce-in-episerver-cms/\">Frederik Vig</a>, <a href=\"http://www.kloojed.com/2010/05/customize-the-tiny-mce-editor-options-in-episerver-cms-6\">Marcus Lindblom</a>, and <a href=\"http://krompaco.nu/alter-default-initoptions-for-tinymce-in-episerver-6/\">Johan Kronberg</a> have covered this in blog posts.\r\n\r\nAlso check out the <a title=\"TinyMCE documentation\" href=\"http://wiki.moxiecode.com/index.php/TinyMCE:Installation\">TinyMCE </a>and <a title=\"EPiServer docs\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Documentation/Items/Tech-Notes/EPiServer-CMS-6/EPiServer-CMS-60/TinyMCE-Developers-Guide/\">EPiServer </a>documentation.','Remove h1 from EPiServer 6 TinyMCE','','inherit','open','open','','226-revision-3','','','2010-10-25 16:20:01','2010-10-25 15:20:01','',226,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/25/226-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(231,1,'2010-10-25 16:20:14','2010-10-25 15:20:14','Today I had a task to remove the \"Heading 1\" and \"Heading 2\" options from the format drop-down in the EPiServer 6 