'2010-10-27 22:44:48','2010-10-27 21:44:48','I had an interesting problem last week when a customer reported that the \"linking pages\" or \"soft links\" feature was not working correctly. This is the warning you get when you try to delete an image that is used somewhere on the site. You can also look at the file summary to see a list of pages that use that file.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-238 alignnone\" title=\"episerver-linking-pages\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-linking-pages.png\" alt=\"Screenshot showing linking pages list\" width=\"530\" height=\"216\" />\r\n\r\nIt turns out that this feature is linked to the page indexing implementation which indexes searchable page properties after a page is published. In this case the property in question had not been set as searchable (via admin mode or <a title=\"More information on using PageTypeBuilder\" href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/01/a-developers-guide-to-pagetypebuilder/\">PageTypeBuilder</a> attribute), which leads to the question of how to get all these page properties indexed without having to republish all the affected pages.\r\n\r\nIt turns out it\'s easy to add pages to the search index via the EPiServer API. I\'ve put the code in a scheduled job s it can be run easily or scheduled.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[ScheduledPlugIn(DisplayName = \"Recreate Page Search Index\", Description = \"Re-adds all pages in the website to the search index.\")]\r\npublic class ReindexingJob : JobBase\r\n{\r\n	public override string Execute()\r\n	{\r\n		var array = new ArrayList();\r\n		var pages = new EPiServer.DataAccess.PageListDB().ListAll();\r\n		foreach (var page in pages)\r\n			array.Add(page.ID);\r\n\r\n		var job = new IndexPageJob((int[])array.ToArray(typeof(int)));\r\n		job.Execute();\r\n\r\n		return String.Format(\"{0} pages have been added to the indexer.\", pages.Count);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThere may be a delay before pages start to be added to the index, which is controlled by the indexingDelayAfterPublish configuration setting in the episerver.config file.\r\n\r\nIndex data is stored in 2 tables, tblKeyword and tblPageKeyword.\r\n\r\nMore information is on EPiServer <a title=\"EPiServer World forum article\" href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40816\">#mce_temp_url#</a>World.','Fixing EPiServer soft links','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision-5','','','2010-10-27 22:44:48','2010-10-27 21:44:48','',237,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/27/237-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(244,1,'2010-10-27 22:53:58','2010-10-27 21:53:58','I had an interesting problem last week when a customer reported that the \"linking pages\" or \"soft links\" feature was not working correctly. This is the warning you get when you try to delete an image that is used somewhere on the site. You can also look at the file summary to see a list of pages that use that file.\n\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-238 alignnone\" title=\"episerver-linking-pages\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-linking-pages.png\" alt=\"Screenshot showing linking pages list\" width=\"530\" height=\"216\" />\n\nIt turns out that this feature is linked to the page indexing implementation which indexes searchable page properties after a page is published. In this case the property in question had not been set as searchable (via admin mode or <a title=\"More information on using PageTypeBuilder\" href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/01/a-developers-guide-to-pagetypebuilder/\">PageTypeBuilder</a> attribute), which leads to the question of how to get all these page properties indexed without having to republish all the affected pages.\n\nIt turns out it\'s easy to add pages to the search index via the EPiServer API. I\'ve put the code in a scheduled job so it can be run easily or scheduled.\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[ScheduledPlugIn(DisplayName = \"Recreate Page Search Index\", Description = \"Re-adds all pages in the website to the search index.\")]\npublic class ReindexingJob : JobBase\n{\n	public override string Execute()\n	{\n		var array = new ArrayList();\n		var pages = new EPiServer.DataAccess.PageListDB().ListAll();\n		foreach (var page in pages)\n			array.Add(page.ID);\n\n		var job = new IndexPageJob((int[])array.ToArray(typeof(int)));\n		job.Execute();\n\n		return String.Format(\"{0} pages have been added to the indexer.\", pages.Count);\n	}\n}</pre>\nThere may be a delay before pages start to be added to the index, which is controlled by the indexingDelayAfterPublish configuration setting in the episerver.config file.\n\nIndex data is stored in 2 tables, tblKeyword and tblPageKeyword.\n\nMore information is <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40816\">on EPiServer World</a>.','Fixing EPiServer soft links','','inherit','open','open','','237-autosave','','','2010-10-27 22:53:58','2010-10-27 21:53:58','',237,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/27/237-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(245,1,'2010-10-27 22:45:22','2010-10-27 21:45:22','I had an interesting problem last week when a customer reported that the \"linking pages\" or \"soft links\" feature was not working correctly. This is the warning you get when you try to delete an image that is used somewhere on the site. You can also look at the file summary to see a list of pages that use that file.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"size-full wp-image-238 alignnone\" title=\"episerver-linking-pages\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/episerver-linking-pages.png\" alt=\"Screenshot showing linking pages list\" width=\"530\" height=\"216\" />\r\n\r\nIt turns out that this feature is linked to the page indexing implementation which indexes searchable page properties after a page is published. In this case the property in question had not been set as searchable (via admin mode or <a title=\"More information on using PageTypeBuilder\" href=\"http://www.frederikvig.com/2010/01/a-developers-guide-to-pagetypebuilder/\">PageTypeBuilder</a> attribute), which leads to the question of how to get all these page properties indexed without having to republish all the affected pages.\r\n\r\nIt turns out it\'s easy to add pages to the search index via the EPiServer API. I\'ve put the code in a scheduled job s it can be run easily or scheduled.\r\n<pre class=\"brush:csharp\">[ScheduledPlugIn(DisplayName = \"Recreate Page Search Index\", Description = \"Re-adds all pages in the website to the search index.\")]\r\npublic class ReindexingJob : JobBase\r\n{\r\n	public override string Execute()\r\n	{\r\n		var array = new ArrayList();\r\n		var pages = new EPiServer.DataAccess.PageListDB().ListAll();\r\n		foreach (var page in pages)\r\n			array.Add(page.ID);\r\n\r\n		var job = new IndexPageJob((int[])array.ToArray(typeof(int)));\r\n		job.Execute();\r\n\r\n		return String.Format(\"{0} pages have been added to the indexer.\", pages.Count);\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nThere may be a delay before pages start to be added to the index, which is controlled by the indexingDelayAfterPublish configuration setting in the episerver.config file.\r\n\r\nIndex data is stored in 2 tables, tblKeyword and tblPageKeyword.\r\n\r\nMore information is <a href=\"http://world.episerver.com/Templates/Forum/Pages/thread.aspx?id=40816\">on EPiServer World</a>.','Fixing EPiServer soft links','','inherit','open','open','','237-revision-6','','','2010-10-27 22:45:22','2010-10-27 21:45:22','',237,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/27/237-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(246,1,'2010-10-02 11:22:24','2010-10-02 10:22:24','I currently have this blog under source control in SVN, but as we\'re using Git more and more at work and I\'m trying to use it more, I decided to migrate the project from SVN to <a title=\"Github site\" href=\"http://github.com\">github</a>. Why Git? Well the obvious benefits are speed in downloading from a remote repository, and there are no .svn folders in all the project folders. And it\'s a distributed system that gives you a local repository to work with, so if the remote server is unavailable (or you don\'t have internet access) you can still use your local repository.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"Getting started with Git and GitHub\" href=\"http://help.github.com/\">The process</a> seems quite simple, install msysgit (Git for Windows), generate a keypair, and set your username. For me the only complicated but there is the SSH keypair - what\'s that for?\r\n<h2>What\'s SSH?</h2>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_Shell\"><strong>Secure Shell</strong> or <strong>SSH</strong> is a <a title=\"Network protocol\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Network_protocol\">network protocol</a> that allows data to be exchanged using a <a title=\"Secure channel\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_channel\">secure channel</a> between two networked device</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote cite=\"http://staff.washington.edu/dittrich/misc/ssh/\">SSH is set of programs which employ public/private key technology for authenticating and encrypting sessions between user accounts on distributed hosts on the Internet.</blockquote>\r\n<h2>And what are public/private keys</h2>\r\nPublic/private key encryption is a frequently used cryptography technique involving:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>a public key that can be given to anyone or transmitted insecurely which can only be used to encrypt information</li>\r\n	<li>a private key that you don\'t give to anyone which can be used to decrypt information</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nUsing this system it is easy for 2 computers to begin securely communicating over an insecure network like the Internet.\r\n\r\nTo send some data (a file) securely, simply request a public key from the recipient, encode the data using the public key and send it. The recipient can decode the data with his private key, and anyone else listening in has no way of decoding the message.\r\n\r\nTo authenticate a user the user must have registered their public key. When a user attempts to authenticate, encrypt a message using their previously registered public key. If the supposed user can decrypt and send back the message they must have the private key, and are probably genuine. (Github seems to employ this technique through SSH)','Git and the Secure Shell (SSH)','Some basic notes on what SSH is and how public/private keys are used.','inherit','open','open','','221-revision-4','','','2010-10-02 11:22:24','2010-10-02 10:22:24','',221,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/02/221-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(247,1,'2010-11-29 20:20:56','2010-11-29 20:20:56','This is my web development learning journal. It\'s a place for me to store useful code and information that I work with so I can refer back to it in the future. It\'s also a learning tool because writing down a problem or solution makes me think about it logically and helps me to understand it.\n\nI\'m a web developer and I work at <a title=\"The Cubeworks site\" href=\"http://www.cubeworks.co.uk\">Cubeworks </a>in <a title=\"Brighton on the map\" href=\"http://maps.google.co.uk/maps?f=q&amp;source=s_q&amp;hl=en&amp;geocode=&amp;q=brighton,+uk&amp;sll=53.800651,-4.064941&amp;sspn=20.824402,57.084961&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;hq=&amp;hnear=Brighton,+East+Sussex,+United+Kingdom&amp;ll=50.819818,-0.131836&amp;spn=22.241089,57.084961&amp;z=5\">Brighton</a>.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-292\" title=\"Jonathan Sewell\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/DSCF3927_small.jpg\" alt=\"Jonathan Sewell\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" />','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-autosave','','','2010-11-29 20:20:56','2010-11-29 20:20:56','',2,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/28/2-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(248,1,'2009-11-13 14:07:02','2009-11-13 14:07:02','This is an example of a WordPress page, you could edit this to put information about yourself or your site so readers know where you are coming from. You can create as many pages like this one or sub-pages as you like and manage all of your content inside of WordPress.','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision','','','2009-11-13 14:07:02','2009-11-13 14:07:02','',2,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2009/11/13/2-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(249,1,'2010-10-28 10:28:24','2010-10-28 09:28:24','This is my web development learning journal. It\'s a place for me to store useful code and information that I work with so I can refer back to it in the future. It\'s also a learning tool because writing down a problem or solution makes me think about it logically and helps me to understand it.\r\n\r\nI\'m a web developer and I work at <a title=\"The Cubeworks site\" href=\"http://www.cubeworks.co.uk\">Cubeworks </a>in Brighton, UK.','About','','inherit','open','open','','2-revision-2','','','2010-10-28 10:28:24','2010-10-28 09:28:24','',2,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/10/28/2-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(250,1,'2010-11-16 15:37:48','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Download and install <a title=\"MySQL workbench download\" href=\"http://wb.mysql.com/\">MySQL Workbench</a> if you don\'t have it. Then <a title=\"Download link\" href=\"http://wordpress.org/download/\">download Wordpress</a> and follow the <a href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress\">Famous 5-minute Install</a>.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_252\" align=\"alignleft\" width=\"589\" caption=\"The Wordpress installation screen\"]<a href=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/wordpress-installation-screen.png\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-252 \" title=\"wordpress-installation-screen\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/wordpress-installation-screen-589x500.png\" alt=\"The Wordpress installation screen\" width=\"589\" height=\"500\" /></a>[/caption]','Create a Wordpress site with IIS