neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\"&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>&lt;section name=\"scriptResourceHandler\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingScriptResourceHandlerSection, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\" requirePermission=\"false\" allowDefinition=\"MachineToApplication\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>&lt;sectionGroup name=\"webServices\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingWebServicesSectionGroup, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\"&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span> &lt;section name=\"jsonSerialization\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingJsonSerializationSection, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\" requirePermission=\"false\" allowDefinition=\"Everywhere\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span> &lt;section name=\"profileService\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingProfileServiceSection, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\" requirePermission=\"false\" allowDefinition=\"MachineToApplication\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span> &lt;section name=\"authenticationService\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingAuthenticationServiceSection, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\" requirePermission=\"false\" allowDefinition=\"MachineToApplication\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span> &lt;section name=\"roleService\" type=\"System.Web.Configuration.ScriptingRoleServiceSection, System.Web.Extensions, Version=3.5.0.0, Culture=neutral, PublicKeyToken=31BF3856AD364E35\" requirePermission=\"false\" allowDefinition=\"MachineToApplication\" /&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\"><span style=\"white-space: pre;\"> </span>&lt;/sectionGroup&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">&lt;/sectionGroup&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">&lt;/sectionGroup&gt;</div>\r\n<div id=\"_mcePaste\">&lt;section name=\"episerver.mail\" type=\"EPiServer.Mail.Configuration.EPiServerMailSection, EPiServer.Mail.Configuration\" /&gt;</div>\r\n</div>','Install EPiServer Mail Manually','','inherit','open','open','','264-revision-8','','','2010-11-26 10:53:46','2010-11-26 10:53:46','',264,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/26/264-revision-8/',0,'revision','',0),(275,1,'2010-11-26 11:06:37','2010-11-26 11:06:37','I need to install EPiServer mail on an existing site. The deployment centre is great for quickly setting up a new site, but not for the way we work. We prefer to have all the EPiServer files in the website, rather than in Windows \"Program Files\". And all the required libraries in a separate library folder and referenced by the Visual Studio project. Then the whole lot can be checked in to source control, pulled down by any other developer on any machine, and crucially by our build server.\n\nI\'ve installed a brand new site on my machine, created a copy of it, then installed EPiServer mail on the new site. I can then use <a title=\"Scooter Softeware\" href=\"http://www.scootersoftware.com\">Beyond Compare</a> to see what the Deployment Centre has done. Here are the results:\n<h3>2 new folders have been added</h3>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-additional-files\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-additional-files.png\" alt=\"Screen shot of new folders\" width=\"256\" height=\"548\" />\n\nA new \"EPiServer\" folder and a new \"EPiServerMail\" folder have been added.\n<h3>A new database and connection string</h3>\nA new database was created for EPiServer mail, and a connection string added to connectionStrings.config.\n<h3>A new config file EPiServerMail.config</h3>\n<pre>&lt;episerver.mail&gt;\n    &lt;sites&gt;\n        &lt;site siteId=\"*\"&gt;\n            &lt;broker brokerName=\"\" brokerHostname=\"episervermail.episerver.com\" brokerIP=\"217.114.81.159\" /&gt;\n            &lt;editor defaultFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" defaultFromName=\"EPiServer Mail\" goMailUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/GoMail.aspx\" mailFromAddress=\"test@company.co.uk\" goMailImageUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/pixel.gif\" encoding=\"iso-8859-1\" editorWebServiceUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/EPiServerMailService.asmx\" unsubscribeUrl=\"http://jonathan-win7:17001/EPiServerMail/Public/Unsubscribe.aspx?rid=§recipientId§&amp;amp;mid=§messageId§\" /&gt;\n            &lt;smtpServer name=\"localhost\" port=\"25\" timeout=\"60\" authMode=\"None\" account=\"\" password=\"\" /&gt;\n        &lt;/site&gt;\n    &lt;/sites&gt;\n&lt;/episerver.mail&gt;</pre>\n<h3>Additions and changes to the bin folder</h3>\nNew files are shown in blue, changed files are shown in red.\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-268\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-bin-changes\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-bin-changes.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"374\" height=\"766\" />\n\nThe changed files have all changed from version <strong>6.0.318.113</strong> to<strong> 6.1.79.0</strong>.\n<h3>Web.config Changes</h3>\nThese changes are too many to reproduce here so I\'ll summarise and upload the 2 config files.\n<ul>\n	<li>new configuration sections registered</li>\n	<li>new nhibernate section</li>\n	<li>new hibernate-configuration section</li>\n	<li>new episerver.common section</li>\n	<li>new episerver.search section</li>\n	<li>new episerver.mail section</li>\n	<li>updated assembly bindings for updated .dll files (EPiServer.Data.Cache etc)</li>\n	<li>new assembly bindings (EPiServer.Mail.Core etc)</li>\n	<li>new role and membership providers registered (EPiServerCommonRoleProvider and EPiServerCommonMembershipProvider)</li>\n	<li>pages section, change enableEventValidation to false</li>\n	<li>new modules in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;modules&gt;</li>\n	<li>new handlers in &lt;system.webServer&gt;&lt;ha&gt;</li>\n	<li>location sections for EPiServerMail and EPiServerMail/Public</li>\n</ul>','Install EPiServer Mail Manually','','inherit','open','open','','264-revision-9','','','2010-11-26 11:06:37','2010-11-26 11:06:37','',264,'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/11/26/264-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(276,1,'2010-11-26 11:08:15','2010-11-26 11:08:15','I need to install EPiServer mail on an existing site. The deployment centre is great for quickly setting up a new site, but not for the way we work. We prefer to have all the EPiServer files in the website, rather than in Windows \"Program Files\". And all the required libraries in a separate library folder and referenced by the Visual Studio project. Then the whole lot can be checked in to source control, pulled down by any other developer on any machine, and crucially by our build server.\n\nI\'ve installed a brand new site on my machine, created a copy of it, then installed EPiServer mail on the new site. I can then use <a title=\"Scooter Softeware\" href=\"http://www.scootersoftware.com\">Beyond Compare</a> to see what the Deployment Centre has done. Here are the results:\n<h3>2 new folders have been added</h3>\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-265\" title=\"EPiServer-mail-additional-files\" src=\"http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/EPiServer-mail-additional-files.png\" alt=\"Screen shot of new folders\" width=\"256\" height=\"548\" />\n\nA new \"EPiServer\" folder and a new \"EPiServerMail\" folder have been added.\n<h3>A new database and connection string</h3>\nA new database was created for EPiServer mail, and a connection string added to connectionStrings.config.\n<h3>A ne